# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics refers to contemporary organizational standards, principles, sets of values, and norms that govern the actions and behavior of individuals in a business organization.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics has two dimensions: normative business ethics and descriptive business ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] As a corporate practice and a career specialization, the field is primarily normative.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Academics attempting to understand business behavior employ descriptive methods.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The range and quantity of business ethical issues reflect the interaction of profit-maximizing behavior with non-economic concerns.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Interest in business ethics accelerated dramatically during the 1980s and 1990s, both within major corporations and within academia.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] For example, most major corporations today promote their commitment to non-economic values under headings such as ethics codes and social responsibility charters.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethics implicitly regulates areas and details of behavior that lie beyond governmental control.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The emergence of large corporations with limited relationships and sensitivity to the communities in which they operate accelerated the development of formal ethics regimes.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Maintaining an ethical status is the responsibility of the manager of the business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics reflect the norms of each historical period.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] As time passes, norms evolve, causing accepted behaviors to become objectionable.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics and the resulting behavior evolved as well.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business was involved in slavery, colonialism, and the Cold War.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The term 'business ethics' came into common use in the United States in the early 1970s.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] By the mid-1980s, at least 500 courses in business ethics reached 40,000 students, using some twenty textbooks and at least ten casebooks supported by professional societies, centers and journals of business ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The Society for Business Ethics was founded in 1980.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] European business schools adopted business ethics after 1987, commencing with the European Business Ethics Network.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In 1982, the first single-authored books in the field appeared.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Firms began highlighting their ethical stature in the late 1980s and early 1990s, possibly in an attempt to distance themselves from the business scandals of the day, such as the savings and loan crisis.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The concept of business ethics caught the attention of academics, media and business firms by the end of the Cold War.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] However, criticism of business practices was attacked for infringing on the freedom of entrepreneurs and critics were accused of supporting communists.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This scuttled the discourse of business ethics both in the media and academia.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The Defense Industry Initiative on Business Ethics and Conduct (DII) was created to support corporate ethical conduct.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This era began the belief and support of self-regulation and free trade, which lifted tariffs and barriers and allowed businesses to merge and divest in an increasingly global atmosphere.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] One of the earliest written treatments of business ethics is found in the *Tirukkuṛaḷ*, a Tamil book dated variously from 300 BCE to the 7th century CE and attributed to Thiruvalluvar.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Many verses discuss business ethics, in particular, verse 113, adapting to a changing environment in verses 474, 426, and 140, learning the intricacies of different tasks in verses 462 and 677.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics reflects the philosophy of business, which one of those aims is to determine the fundamental purposes of a company.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business purpose expresses the company's reason for existing.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Modern discussion on the purpose of business has been freshened by views from thinkers such as Richard R.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ellesworth, Peter Drucker, and Nikos Mourkogiannis: Earlier views, such as Milton Friedman's, held that the purpose of a business organization is to make a profit for shareholders.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Nevertheless, the purpose of maximizing shareholders' wealth often "fails to energize employees".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] On the other hand, if a company's purpose is to maximize shareholder returns, then sacrificing profits for other concerns is a violation of its fiduciary responsibility.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Corporate entities are legal persons but this does not mean they are legally entitled to all of the rights and liabilities of natural persons.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethics are the rules or standards that govern our decisions on a daily basis.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Many consider "ethics" with conscience or a simplistic sense of "right" and "wrong".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Others would say that ethics is an internal code that governs an individual's conduct, ingrained into each person by family, faith, tradition, community, laws, and personal mores.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Corporations and professional organizations, particularly licensing boards, generally will have a written code of ethics that governs standards of professional conduct expected of all in the field.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] "Law" and "ethics" are not synonymous, nor are the "legal" and "ethical" courses of action in a given situation necessarily the same.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Statutes and regulations passed by legislative bodies and administrative boards set forth the "law".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Slavery was once legal in the US, but one certainly would not say enslaving another was an "ethical" act.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Economist Milton Friedman wrote that corporate executives' "responsibility ... generally will be to make as much money as possible while conforming to their basic rules of the society, both those embodied in law and those embodied in ethical custom".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Friedman also said, "the only entities who can have responsibilities are individuals ...
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] A business cannot have responsibilities.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] So the question is, do corporate executives, provided they stay within the law, have responsibilities in their business activities other than to make as much money for their stockholders as possible?
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] And my answer to that is, no, they do not." This view is known as the Friedman doctrine.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] A multi-country 2011 survey found support for this view among the "informed public" ranging from 30 to 80%.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ronald Duska and Jacques Cory have described Friedman's argument as consequentialist or utilitarian rather than pragmatic: Friedman's argument implies that unrestrained corporate freedom would benefit the most people in the long term.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] So Friedman was wrong that making a profit is the only concern of business, Duska argued.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Peter Drucker once said, "There is neither a separate ethics of business nor is one needed", implying that standards of personal ethics cover all business situations.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] However, Drucker in another instance said that the ultimate responsibility of company directors is not to harm—*primum non nocere*.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Philosopher and author Ayn Rand has put forth her idea of rational egoism, which also applies to business ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] She stresses that the position of the entrepreneur, who has to be responsible for his own happiness and the business is a means to said happiness, where the entrepreneur is not required to serve the interest of anyone else and no one is entitled to his/her work.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Another view of business is that it must exhibit corporate social responsibility (CSR): an umbrella term indicating that an ethical business must act as a responsible citizen of the communities in which it operates, even at the cost of profits or other goals.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In the US and most other nations, corporate entities are legally treated as persons in some respects.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] For example, they can hold title to property, sue and be sued and are subject to taxation, although their free speech rights are limited.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This can be interpreted to imply that they have independent ethical responsibilities.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Duska argued that stakeholders expect a business to be ethical and that violating that expectation must be counterproductive for the business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethical issues include the rights and duties between a company and its employees, suppliers, customers and neighbors, its fiduciary responsibility to its shareholders.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Issues concerning relations between different companies include hostile takeovers and industrial espionage.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Related issues include corporate governance, corporate social entrepreneurship, political contributions, legal issues such as the ethical debate over introducing a crime of corporate manslaughter, and the marketing of corporations' ethics policies.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] According to research published by the Institute of Business Ethics and Ipsos MORI in late 2012, the three major areas of public concern regarding business ethics in Britain are executive pay, corporate tax avoidance and bribery and corruption.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The ethical standards of an entire organization can be damaged if a corporate psychopath is in charge.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This will affect not only the company and its outcome but also the employees who work under a corporate psychopath.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The way a corporate psychopath can rise in a company is by their manipulation, scheming, and bullying.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] They do this in a way that can hide their true character and intentions within a company.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Fundamentally, finance is a social science discipline.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The discipline borders behavioral economics, sociology, economics, accounting and management.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] It concerns technical issues such as the mix of debt and equity, dividend policy, the evaluation of alternative investment projects, options, futures, swaps, and other derivatives, portfolio diversification and many others.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Finance is often mistaken by people to be a discipline free from ethical burdens.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The 2008 financial crisis caused critics to challenge the ethics of the executives in charge of U.S. and European financial institutions and financial regulatory bodies.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Finance ethics is overlooked for another reason—issues in finance are often addressed as matters of law rather than ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Aristotle said, "the end and purpose of the polis is the good life".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Adam Smith characterized the good life in terms of material goods and intellectual and moral excellences of character.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] However, a section of economists influenced by the ideology of neoliberalism interpreted the objective of economics to be the maximization of economic growth through accelerated consumption and production of goods and services.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberal ideology promoted finance from its position as a component of economics to its core.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Proponents of the ideology hold that unrestricted financial flows, if redeemed from the shackles of "financial repressions", best help impoverished nations to grow.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The theory holds that open financial systems accelerate economic growth by encouraging foreign capital inflows, thereby enabling higher levels of savings, investment, employment, productivity and "welfare", along with containing corruption.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberals recommended that governments open their financial systems to the global market with minimal regulation over capital flows.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The recommendations, however, met with criticisms from various schools of ethical philosophy.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some pragmatic ethicists found these claims to be unfalsifiable and a priori, although neither of these makes the recommendations false or unethical per se.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Raising economic growth to the highest value necessarily means that welfare is subordinate, although advocates dispute this, saying that economic growth provides more welfare than known alternatives.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Since history shows that neither regulated nor unregulated firms always behave ethically, neither regime offers an ethical panacea.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberal recommendations to developing countries to unconditionally open up their economies to transnational finance corporations were fiercely contested by some ethicists.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The claim that deregulation and the opening up of economies would reduce corruption was also contested.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Dobson observes, "a rational agent is simply one who pursues personal material advantage ad infinitum.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In essence, to be rational in finance is to be individualistic, materialistic, and competitive.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business is a game played by individuals, as with all games, the object is to win, and winning is measured in terms solely of material wealth.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Within the discipline, this rationality concept is never questioned, and has indeed become the theory-of-the-firm's sine qua non".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Financial ethics, is in this view, a mathematical function of shareholder wealth.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Such simplifying assumptions were once necessary for the construction of mathematically robust models.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] However, signalling theory and agency theory extended the paradigm to greater realism.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Fairness in trading practices, trading conditions, financial contracting, sales practices, consultancy services, tax payments, internal audit, external audit and executive compensation also fall under the umbrella of finance and accounting.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Particular corporate ethical/legal abuses include: creative accounting, earnings management, misleading financial analysis, insider trading, securities fraud, bribery/kickbacks and facilitation payments.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Outside of corporations, bucket shops and forex scams are criminal manipulations of financial markets.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Cases include accounting scandals, Enron, WorldCom and Satyam.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Human resource management occupies the sphere of activity of recruitment selection, orientation, performance appraisal, training and development, industrial relations and health and safety issues.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Business Ethicists differ in their orientation towards labor ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some assess human resource policies according to whether they support an egalitarian workplace and the dignity of labor.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Issues including employment itself, privacy, compensation in accord with comparable worth, collective bargaining (and/or its opposite) can be seen either as inalienable rights or as negotiable.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Discrimination by age (preferring the young or the old), gender/sexual harassment, race, religion, disability, weight and attractiveness.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] A common approach to remedying discrimination is affirmative action.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Once hired, employees have the right to the occasional cost-of-living increases, as well as raises based on merit.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Promotions, however, are not a right, and there are often fewer openings than qualified applicants.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] It may seem unfair if an employee who has been with a company longer is passed over for a promotion, but it is not unethical.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] It is only unethical if the employer did not give the employee proper consideration or used improper criteria for the promotion.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Each employer should know the distinction between what is unethical and what is illegal.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] If an action is illegal, it is breaking the law, but if an action seems morally incorrect, that is unethical.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In the workplace, what is unethical does not mean illegal and should follow the guidelines put in place by OSHA (Occupational Safety and Health Administration), EEOC (Equal Employment Opportunity Commission), and other law-binding entities.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Potential employees have ethical obligations to employers, involving intellectual property protection and whistle-blowing.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Employers must consider workplace safety, which may involve modifying the workplace or providing appropriate training or hazard disclosure.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This differentiates based on the location and type of work that is taking place and may require compliance with the standards to protect employees and non-employees under workplace safety.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Larger economic issues such as immigration, trade policy, globalization and trade unionism affect workplaces and have an ethical dimension, but are often beyond the purview of individual companies.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Trade unions, for example, may push employers to establish due process for workers, but may also cause job loss by demanding unsustainable compensation and work rules.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Among the many people management strategies that companies employ are a "soft" approach that regards employees as a source of creative energy and participants in workplace decision-making, a "hard" version explicitly focused on control and Theory Z that emphasizes philosophy, culture and consensus.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some studies claim that sustainable success requires a humanely treated and satisfied workforce.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In the procurement field, ethical behaviour includes adherence to the principle of fairness, avoidance of preferential treatment, and the elimination of malpractice in relation to suppliers and their workforces.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply, which provides ethical procurement assessment for its members, notes that "it's important to recognise that being ethical isn't just within the business community, but consumers can also make ethical choices in their buying decisions".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics came of age only as late as the 1990s.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics was approached from ethical perspectives of virtue or virtue ethics, deontology, consequentialism, pragmatism and relativism.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethics in marketing deals with the principles, values and/or ideas by which marketers (and marketing institutions) ought to act.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics is also a contested terrain, beyond the previously described issue of potential conflicts between profitability and other concerns.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] According to Borgerson and Schroeder (2008), marketing can influence individuals' perceptions of and interactions with other people, implying an ethical responsibility to avoid distorting those perceptions and interactions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics involves pricing practices, including illegal actions such as price fixing and legal actions, including price discrimination and price skimming.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Certain promotional activities have drawn fire, including greenwashing, bait and switch, shilling, viral marketing, spam (electronic), pyramid schemes and multi-level marketing.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Advertising has raised objections about attack ads, subliminal messages, sex in advertising and marketing in schools.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Scholars in business and management have paid much attention to the ethical issues in the different forms of relationships between organizations such as buyer-supplier relationships, networks, alliances, or joint ventures.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Drawing in particular on transaction cost theory and agency theory, they note the risk of opportunistic and unethical practices between partners through, for instance, shirking, poaching, and other deceitful behaviors.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In turn, research on inter-organizational relationships has observed the role of formal and informal mechanisms to both prevent unethical practices and mitigate their consequences.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] It especially discusses the importance of formal contracts and relational norms between partners to manage ethical issues.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Being the most important element of a business, stakeholders' main concern is to determine whether or not the business is behaving ethically or unethically.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The business's actions and decisions should be primarily ethical before they become an ethical or even legal issue.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This area of business ethics usually deals with the duties of a company to ensure that products and production processes do not needlessly cause harm.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Since a few goods and services can be produced and consumed with zero risks, determining the ethical course can be difficult.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In some cases, consumers demand products that harm them, such as tobacco products.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Production may have environmental impacts, including pollution, habitat destruction and urban sprawl.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The downstream effects of technologies, such as nuclear power, genetically modified food and mobile phones, may not be well understood.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] While the precautionary principle may prohibit introducing new technology whose consequences are not fully understood, that principle would have prohibited the newest technology introduced since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Product testing protocols have been attacked for violating the rights of both humans and animals.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some sources that provide information on companies that are environmentally responsible or do not test on animals.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The etymological root of property is the Latin *proprius*, which refers to 'nature', 'quality', 'one's own', 'special characteristic', 'proper', 'intrinsic', 'inherent', 'regular', 'normal', 'genuine', 'thorough, complete, perfect' etc.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The word property is value-loaded and associated with the personal qualities of propriety and respectability, and it also implies questions relating to ownership.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] A 'proper' person owns and is true to herself or himself, and is thus genuine, perfect and pure.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Modern discourse on property emerged by the turn of the 17th century within theological discussions of that time.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] For instance, John Locke justified property rights, saying that God had made "the earth, and all inferior creatures, [in] common to all men".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In 1802, utilitarian Jeremy Bentham stated, "property and law are born together and die together".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] One argument for property ownership is that it enhances individual liberty by extending the line of non-interference by the state or others around the person.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Seen from this perspective, property rights are absolute and property has a special and distinctive character that precedes its legal protection.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Blackstone conceptualized property as the "sole and despotic dominion which one man claims and exercises over the external things of the world, in total exclusion of the right of any other individual in the universe".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] During the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, slavery spread to European colonies, including America, where colonial legislatures defined the legal status of slaves as a form of property.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Combined with theological justification, the property was taken to be essentially natural, ordained by God.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Wiecek says, "Yet slavery was more clearly and explicitly established under the Constitution than it had been under the Articles".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In an 1857 judgment, US Supreme Court Chief Justice Roger B.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberals hold that private property rights are a non-negotiable natural right.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Rose finds, "'Property' is only an effect, a construction, of relationships between people, meaning that its objective character is contestable.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In common parlance, property rights involve a bundle of rights including occupancy, use and enjoyment, and the right to sell, devise, give, or lease all or part of these rights.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Custodians of property have obligations as well as rights.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Menon claims that the autonomous individual, responsible for his/her own existence, is a cultural construct moulded by Western culture rather than the truth about the human condition.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Penner views property as an "illusion"—a "normative phantasm" without substance.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In the neoliberal literature, the property is part of the private side of a public/private dichotomy and acts as a counterweight to state power.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Davies counters that "any space may be subject to plural meanings or appropriations which do not necessarily come into conflict".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Private property has never been a universal doctrine, although since the end of the Cold War, it has become nearly so.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some societies, e.g., Native American bands, held land, if not all property, in common.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] When groups came into conflict, the victor often appropriated the loser's property.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The rights paradigm tended to stabilize the distribution of property holdings on the presumption that title had been lawfully acquired.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Property does not exist in isolation, and neither do property rights.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Bryan claimed that property rights describe relations among people and not just relations between people and things.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Singer holds that the idea that owners have no legal obligations to others wrongly supposes that property rights hardly ever conflict with other legally protected interests.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Singer continues implying that legal realists "did not take the character and structure of social relations as an important independent factor in choosing the rules that govern market life".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The ethics of property rights begins with recognizing the vacuous nature of the notion of property.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Intellectual property (IP) encompasses expressions of ideas, thoughts, codes, and information.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] "Intellectual property rights" (IPR) treat IP as a kind of real property, subject to analogous protections, rather than as a reproducible good or service.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Boldrin and Levine argue that "government does not ordinarily enforce monopolies for producers of other goods.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This is because it is widely recognized that a monopoly creates many social costs.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Intellectual monopoly is no different in this respect.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] International standards relating to intellectual property rights are enforced through the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In the US, IP other than copyrights is regulated by the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The US Constitution included the power to protect intellectual property, empowering the Federal government "to promote the progress of science and useful arts, by securing for limited times to authors and inventors the exclusive right to their respective writings and discoveries".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Boldrin and Levine see no value in such state-enforced monopolies, stating, "we ordinarily think of innovative monopoly as an oxymoron.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Further, they comment, 'intellectual property' "is not like ordinary property at all, but constitutes a government grant of a costly and dangerous private monopoly over ideas.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] We show through theory and example that intellectual monopoly is not necessary for innovation and, as a practical matter, is damaging to growth, prosperity, and liberty".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Steelman defends patent monopolies, writing, "Consider prescription drugs, for instance.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Such drugs have benefited millions of people, improving or extending their lives.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] One attack on IPR is moral rather than utilitarian, claiming that inventions are mostly a collective, cumulative, path-dependent, social creation and therefore, no one person or firm should be able to monopolize them even for a limited period.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The opposing argument is that the benefits of innovation arrive sooner when patents encourage innovators and their investors to increase their commitments.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Machlup concluded that patents do not have the intended effect of enhancing innovation.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Mindeli and Pipiya argued that the knowledge economy is an economy of abundance because it relies on the "infinite potential" of knowledge and ideas rather than on the limited resources of natural resources, labor and capital.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Allison envisioned an egalitarian distribution of knowledge.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Kinsella claimed that IPR create artificial scarcity and reduce equality.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Bouckaert wrote, "Natural scarcity is that which follows from the relationship between man and nature.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Scarcity is natural when it is possible to conceive of it before any human, institutional, or contractual arrangement.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Artificial scarcity, on the other hand, is the outcome of such arrangements.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Artificial scarcity can hardly serve as a justification for the legal framework that causes that scarcity.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Such an argument would be completely circular.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] On the contrary, artificial scarcity itself needs a justification".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Corporations fund much IP creation and can acquire IP they do not create, to which Menon and others have objected.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Andersen claims that IPR has increasingly become an instrument in eroding the public domain.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Notable IP copyright cases include *A&M Records, Inc. v.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ashcroft*, and Disney's lawsuit against the Air Pirates.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] While business ethics emerged as a field in the 1970s, international business ethics did not emerge until the late 1990s, looking back on the international developments of that decade.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Many new practical issues arose out of the international context of business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Theoretical issues such as the cultural relativity of ethical values receive more emphasis in this field.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Other, older issues can be grouped here as well.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Foreign countries often use dumping as a competitive threat, selling products at prices lower than their normal value.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This can lead to problems in domestic markets, as it becomes difficult for them to compete with the pricing set by foreign markets.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In 2009, the International Trade Commission conducted research on anti-dumping laws.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Dumping is often seen as an ethical issue, as larger companies take advantage of other, less economically advanced companies.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethical issues often arise in business settings, whether through business transactions or forming new business relationships.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] It also has a huge focus in the auditing field, whereby the type of verification can be directly dictated by ethical theory.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] An ethical issue in a business atmosphere may refer to any situation that requires business associates as individuals, or as a group (for example, a department or firm) to evaluate the morality of specific actions, and subsequently, make a decision among the choices.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some ethical issues of particular concern in today's evolving business market include such topics as honesty, integrity, professional behaviors, environmental issues, harassment, and fraud, to name a few.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The ethical issues associated with honesty are widespread and vary greatly in business, from the misuse of company time or resources to lying with malicious intent, engaging in bribery, or creating conflicts of interest within an organization.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Honesty encompasses the truthful speech and actions of an individual wholly.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Some cultures and belief systems even consider honesty to be an essential pillar of life, such as Confucianism and Buddhism (referred to as sacca, part of the Four Noble Truths).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Many employees lie in order to reach goals, avoid assignments or negative issues; however, sacrificing honesty in order to gain status or reap rewards poses potential problems for the overall ethical culture organization, and jeopardizes organizational goals in the long run.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Using company time or resources for personal use is also commonly viewed as unethical because it boils down to stealing from the company.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The misuse of resources costs companies billions of dollars each year, averaging about 4.25 hours per week of stolen time alone, and employees' abuse of Internet services is another main concern.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Bribery, on the other hand, is not only considered unethical in business practices, but it is also illegal.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In accordance with this, the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act was established in 1977 to deter international businesses from giving or receiving unwarranted payments and gifts that were intended to influence the decisions of executives and political officials.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Although small payments known as facilitation payments will not be considered unlawful under the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act if they are used towards regular public governance activities, such as permits or licenses.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Many aspects of the work environment influence an individual's decision-making regarding ethics in the business world.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] When an individual is on the path of growing a company, many outside influences can pressure them to perform a certain way.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The core of a person's performance in the workplace is rooted in their personal code of behavior.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] A person's personal code of ethics encompasses many different qualities such as integrity, honesty, communication, respect, compassion, and common goals.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In addition, the ethical standards set forth by a person's superior(s) often translate into their own code of ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The company's policy is the 'umbrella' of ethics that plays a major role in the personal development and decision-making processes that people make with respect to ethical behavior.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] National economic conditions often shape corporate ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] In environments marked by high poverty, large corporations may continue to expand, while smaller firms face significant survival challenges.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] This pressure can lead leadership to explore unconventional or unethical avenues to secure business opportunities.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Similarly, social media has become a primary influence on ethical standards.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The constant flow of information and public opinion can pressure individuals to conform to perceived norms.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Consequently, fast-moving digital trends and the drive for instant engagement can alter how people evaluate moral and professional decisions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Political economy and political philosophy have ethical implications, particularly regarding the distribution of economic benefits.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] John Rawls and Robert Nozick are both notable contributors.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] For example, Rawls has been interpreted as offering a critique of offshore outsourcing on social contract grounds.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Laws are the written statutes, codes, and opinions of government organizations by which citizens, businesses, and persons present within a jurisdiction are expected to govern themselves or face legal sanction.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Sanctions for violating the law can include (a) civil penalties, such as fines, pecuniary damages, and loss of licenses, property, rights, or privileges; (b) criminal penalties, such as fines, probation, imprisonment, or a combination thereof; or (c) both civil and criminal penalties.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Very often, it is held that business is not bound by any ethics other than abiding by the law.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Milton Friedman is the pioneer of the view.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] He held that corporations have the obligation to make a profit within the framework of the legal system, nothing more.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Friedman made it explicit that the duty of the business leaders is "to make as much money as possible while conforming to the basic rules of the society, both those embodied in the law and those embodied in ethical custom".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Ethics for Friedman is nothing more than abiding by customs and laws.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] The reduction of ethics to abidance to laws and customs, however, has drawn serious criticisms.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Counter to Friedman's logic, it is observed that legal procedures are technocratic, bureaucratic, rigid and obligatory whereas ethical act is conscientious, voluntary choice beyond normativity.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] For Law against crime to be passed, the crime must have happened.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Laws are blind to the crimes undefined in them.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Further, as per law, "conduct is not criminal unless forbidden by law which gives advance warning that such conduct is criminal".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Also, the law presumes the accused is innocent until proven guilty and that the state must establish the guilt of the accused beyond a reasonable doubt.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] As per liberal laws followed in most of the democracies, until the government prosecutor proves the firm guilty with the limited resources available to her, the accused is considered to be innocent.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p01] Though the liberal premises of law are necessary to protect individuals from being persecuted by the government, it is not a sufficient mechanism to make firms morally accountable.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] As part of more comprehensive compliance and ethics programs, many companies have formulated internal policies pertaining to the ethical conduct of employees.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] These policies can be simple exhortations in broad, highly generalized language (typically called a corporate ethics statement), or they can be more detailed policies, containing specific behavioral requirements (typically called corporate ethics codes).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] They are generally meant to identify the company's expectations of workers and to offer guidance on handling some of the more common ethical problems that might arise in the course of doing business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] It is hoped that having such a policy will lead to greater ethical awareness, consistency in application, and the avoidance of ethical disasters.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] An increasing number of companies also require employees to attend seminars regarding business conduct, which often include discussion of the company's policies, specific case studies, and legal requirements.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Some companies even require their employees to sign agreements stating that they will abide by the company's rules of conduct.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Many companies are assessing the environmental factors that can lead employees to engage in unethical conduct.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] A competitive business environment may call for unethical behavior.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Lying has become expected in fields such as trading.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] An example of this is the issues surrounding the unethical actions of the Salomon Brothers.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Not everyone supports corporate policies that govern ethical conduct.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Some claim that ethical problems are better dealt with by depending upon employees to use their own judgment.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Others believe that corporate ethics policies are primarily rooted in utilitarian concerns and that they are mainly to limit the company's legal liability or to curry public favor by giving the appearance of being a good corporate citizen.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Ideally, the company will avoid a lawsuit because its employees will follow the rules.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Should a lawsuit occur, the company can claim that the problem would not have arisen if the employee had only followed the code properly.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Some corporations have tried to burnish their ethical image by creating whistle-blower protections, such as anonymity.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In the case of Citi, they call this the Ethics Hotline.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Though it is unclear whether firms such as Citi take offences reported to these hotlines seriously or not.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Sometimes there is a disconnection between the company's code of ethics and the company's actual practices.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Thus, whether or not such conduct is explicitly sanctioned by management, at worst, this makes the policy duplicitous, and, at best, it is merely a marketing tool.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Jones and Parker wrote, "Most of what we read under the name business ethics is either sentimental common sense or a set of excuses for being unpleasant." Many manuals are procedural form-filling exercises, unconcerned about the real ethical dilemmas.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] For instance, the US Department of Commerce ethics program treats business ethics as a set of instructions and procedures to be followed by 'ethics officers'.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Some others claim that being ethical is just for the sake of being ethical.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Business ethicists may trivialize the subject, offering standard answers that do not reflect the situation's complexity.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Ethics codes often state a company's view on DEI (diversity, equity, inclusivity).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In 2025, some companies began changing their ethics policies to reduce the focus on DEI, and some companies have decided to completely eliminate DEI from their policies.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Following a series of fraud, corruption, and abuse scandals that affected the United States defense industry in the mid-1980s, the Defense Industry Initiative (DII) was created to promote ethical business practices and ethics management in multiple industries.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Subsequent to these scandals, many organizations began appointing ethics officers (also referred to as "compliance" officers).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In 1991, the Ethics & Compliance Officer Association —originally the Ethics Officer Association (EOA)—was founded at the Center for Business Ethics at Bentley University as a professional association for ethics and compliance officers.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The 1991 passing of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines for Organizations in 1991 was another factor in many companies appointing ethics/compliance officers.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] These guidelines, intended to assist judges with sentencing, set standards organizations must follow to obtain a reduction in sentence if they are convicted of a federal offense.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Following the high-profile corporate scandals of companies like Enron, WorldCom and Tyco between 2001 and 2004, and following the passage of the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, many small and mid-sized companies also began to appoint ethics officers.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Often reporting to the chief executive officer, ethics officers focus on uncovering or preventing unethical and illegal actions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This is accomplished by assessing the ethical implications of the company's activities, making recommendations on ethical policies, and disseminating information to employees.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The effectiveness of ethics officers is not clear.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The establishment of an ethics officer position is likely to be insufficient in driving ethical business practices without a corporate culture that values ethical behavior.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] These values and behaviors should be consistently and systemically supported by those at the top of the organization.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Employees with strong community involvement, loyalty to employers, superiors or owners, smart work practices, and trust among the team members do inculcate a corporate culture.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Many corporate and business strategies now include sustainability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In addition to the traditional environmental 'green' sustainability concerns, business ethics practices have expanded to include social sustainability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Social sustainability focuses on issues related to human capital in the business supply chain, such as workers' rights, working conditions, child labor, and human trafficking.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Incorporation of these considerations is increasing, as consumers and procurement officials demand documentation of a business's compliance with national and international initiatives, guidelines, and standards.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Initiatives in sustainability encompass "green" topics, as well as social sustainability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Tao *et al*. refer to a variety of "green" business practices, including green strategy, green design, green production and green operation.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] There are however, many different ways in which sustainability initiatives can be implemented by a company.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] An organization can implement sustainability initiatives by improving its operations and manufacturing processes so as to make it more aligned with environmental, social, and governance issues.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Walmart has made commitments to doubling its truck fleet efficiency by 2015 by replacing 2/3rds of its fleet with more fuel-efficient trucks, including hybrids.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Dell has integrated alternative, recycled, and recyclable materials in its products and packaging design, improving energy efficiency and design for end-of-life and recyclability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Dell plans to reduce the energy intensity of its product portfolio by 80% by 2020.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The board of a company can decide to lower executive compensation by a given percentage, and give the percentage of compensation to a specific cause.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This is an effort which can only be implemented from the top, as it will affect the compensation of all executives in the company.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In Alcoa, an aluminum company based in the US, "1/5th of executive cash compensation is tied to safety, diversity, and environmental stewardship, which includes greenhouse gas emission reductions and energy efficiency" (Best Practices).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This is not usually the case for most companies, where we see the board take a uniform step towards the environment, social, and governance issues.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This is only the case for companies that are directly linked to utilities, energy, or material industries, something which Alcoa as an aluminum company, falls in line with.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Instead, formal committees focused on the environment, social, and governance issues are more usually seen in governance committees and audit committees, rather than the board of directors.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] "According to research analysis done by Pearl Meyer in support of the NACD 2017 Director Compensation Report shows that among 1,400 public companies reviewed, only slightly more than five percent of boards have a designated committee to address ESG issues." (How compensation can).
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Similar to board leadership, creating steering committees and other types of committees specialized for sustainability, senior executives are identified who are held accountable for meeting and constantly improving sustainability goals.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Introducing bonus schemes that reward executives for meeting non-financial performance, goals including safety targets, greenhouse gas emissions, reduction targets, and goals engaging stakeholders to help shape the company's public policy positions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Exelon have implemented policies like this.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Other companies will keep sustainability within their strategy and goals, presenting findings at shareholder meetings, and actively tracking metrics on sustainability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as PepsiCo, Heineken, and FIFCO take steps in this direction to implement sustainability initiatives.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Coca-Cola have actively tried to improve their efficiency of water usage, hiring 3rd party auditors to evaluate their water management approach.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] FIFCO has also successfully led water-management initiatives.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Implementation of sustainability projects through directly appealing to employees (typically through the human resource department) is another option for companies to implement sustainability.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This involves integrating sustainability into the company culture, with hiring practices and employee training.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] General Electric is a company that is taking the lead in implementing initiatives in this manner.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Bank of America directly engaged employees by implementing LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) certified buildings, with a fifth of its building meeting these certifications.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Establishing requirements for not only internal operations but also first-tier suppliers as well as second-tier suppliers to help drive environmental and social expectations further down the supply chain.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Starbucks, FIFCO and Ford Motor Company have implemented requirements that suppliers must meet to win their business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Starbucks has led efforts in engaging suppliers and local communities where they operate to accelerate investment in sustainable farming.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Starbucks set a goal of ethically sourcing 100% of its coffee beans by 2015.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] By revealing decision-making data about how sustainability was reached, companies can give away insights that can help others across the industry and beyond make more sustainable decisions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Nike launched its "making app" in 2013, which released data about the sustainability of the materials it was using.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This ultimately allows other companies to make more sustainable design decisions and create lower-impact products.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] As an academic discipline, business ethics emerged in the 1970s.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Since no academic business ethics journals or conferences existed, researchers published in general management journals and attended general conferences.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Over time, specialized peer-reviewed journals appeared, and more researchers entered the field.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Corporate scandals in the early 2000s increased the field's popularity.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] As of 2009, sixteen academic journals devoted to various business ethics issues existed, with *Journal of Business Ethics* and *Business Ethics Quarterly* considered the leaders.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] *Journal of Business Ethics Education* publishes articles specifically about education in business ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The International Business Development Institute is a global non-profit organization that represents 217 nations and all 50 United States.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] It offers a Charter in Business Development that focuses on ethical business practices and standards.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] The Charter is directed by Harvard University, MIT, and Fulbright Scholars, and it includes graduate-level coursework in economics, politics, marketing, management, technology, and legal aspects of business development as it pertains to business ethics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] IBDI also oversees the International Business Development Institute of Asia, which provides individuals living in 20 Asian nations the opportunity to earn the Charter.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] In Sharia law, followed by many Muslims, banking specifically prohibits charging interest on loans.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Traditional Confucian thought discourages profit-seeking.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] According to the article "Theory of the real economy", there is a narrower point of view from the Christian faith towards the relationship between ethics and religious traditions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] This article stresses how Christianity is capable of establishing reliable boundaries for financial institutions.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics receives an extensive treatment in Jewish thought and Rabbinic literature, both from an ethical (*Mussar*) and a legal (*Halakha*) perspective; see the article *Jewish business ethics* for further discussion.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] According to the article "Indian Philosophy and Business Ethics: A Review", by Chandrani Chattopadyay, Hindus follow "Dharma" as Business Ethics and unethical business practices are termed "Adharma".
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Businessmen are supposed to maintain steadiness, self-purification, non-violence, concentration, clarity and control over their senses.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Books like the Bhagavat Gita and the Arthashastra contribute a lot towards the conduct of ethical business.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics is related to philosophy of economics, the branch of the philosophy that deals with the philosophical, political, and ethical underpinnings of business and economics.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics is also related to political economy, which is an economic analysis from political and historical perspectives.
[src:energy-management/business-ethics-p02] Political economy deals with the distributive consequences of economic actions.
[src:energy-management/ceo] A **chief executive officer** (**CEO**), also known as a **chief executive** or **managing director**, is the top-ranking corporate officer charged with the management of a company or a nonprofit organization.
[src:energy-management/ceo] CEOs find roles in various organizations, including public and private corporations, nonprofit organizations, and even some government organizations (notably state-owned enterprises).
[src:energy-management/ceo] The governor and CEO of a corporation or company typically report to the board of directors and are charged with maximizing the value of the business, which may include maximizing the profitability, market share, revenue, or another financial metric.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the nonprofit and government sector, CEOs typically aim at achieving outcomes related to the organization's mission, usually provided by legislation.
[src:energy-management/ceo] CEOs are also frequently assigned the role of the main manager of the organization and the highest-ranking officer in the C-suite.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The term "chief executive officer" is attested as early as 1782, when an ordinance of the Congress of the Confederation of the United States of America used the term to refer to governors and other leaders of the executive branches of each of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In draft additions to the *Oxford English Dictionary* published online in 2011, the *Dictionary* says that the use of "CEO" as an acronym for a chief executive officer originated in Australia, with the first attestation being in 1914.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The first American usage cited is from 1972.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The responsibilities of an organization's CEO are set by the organization's board of directors or other authority, depending on the organization's structure.
[src:energy-management/ceo] They can be far-reaching or quite limited, and are typically enshrined in a formal delegation of authority regarding business administration.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Typically, responsibilities include being an active decision-maker on business strategy and other key policy issues, as well as leader, manager, and executor roles.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The communicator role can involve speaking to the press and the public, as well as to the organization's management and employees.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The decision-making role entails making high-level decisions regarding policy and strategy.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The CEO is responsible for implementing the goals, targets, and strategic objectives as determined by the board of directors.
[src:energy-management/ceo] As an executive officer of the company, the CEO reports the status of the business to the board of directors, motivates employees, and drives change within the organization.
[src:energy-management/ceo] As a manager, the CEO presides over the organization's day-to-day operations.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The CEO is the person who is ultimately accountable for a company's business decisions, including those in operations, marketing, business development, finance, human resources, etc.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The CEO of a political party is often entrusted with fundraising, particularly for election campaigns.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The use of the CEO title may be used by for-profit companies or non-profit or charitable organisations, such as the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In some countries, there is a dual board system with two separate boards, one executive board for the day-to-day business and one supervisory board for control purposes (selected by the shareholders).
[src:energy-management/ceo] In these countries, the CEO presides over the executive board and the chairperson presides over the supervisory board, and these two roles will always be held by different people.
[src:energy-management/ceo] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board.
[src:energy-management/ceo] This allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the United States, the board of directors (elected by the shareholders) is often equivalent to the supervisory board, while the executive board may often be known as the executive committee (the division/subsidiary heads and C-level officers that report directly to the CEO).
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the United States, and in business, the executive officers are usually the top officers of a corporation, the chief executive officer (CEO) being the best-known type.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The definition varies; for instance, the California Corporate Disclosure Act defines "executive officers" as the five most highly compensated officers not also sitting on the board of directors.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the case of a sole proprietorship, an executive officer is the sole proprietor.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the case of a partnership, an executive officer is a managing partner, senior partner, or administrative partner.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the case of a limited liability company, an executive officer is any member, manager, or officer.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Depending on the organization, a CEO may have several subordinate executives to help run the day-to-day administration of the company, each of whom has specific functional responsibilities referred to as senior executives, executive officers, or corporate officers.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Subordinate executives are given different titles in different organizations, but one common category of subordinate executive, if the CEO is also the president, is the vice president (VP).
[src:energy-management/ceo] An organization may have more than one vice president, each tasked with a different area of responsibility (e.g., VP of finance, VP of human resources).
[src:energy-management/ceo] Examples of subordinate executive officers who typically report to the CEO include the chief operating officer (COO), chief financial officer (CFO), chief strategy officer (CSO), chief marketing officer (CMO), and chief business officer (CBO).
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the US, the term "chief executive officer" is used primarily in business, whereas the term "executive director" is used primarily in the not-for-profit sector.
[src:energy-management/ceo] These terms are generally mutually exclusive and refer to distinct legal duties and responsibilities.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The CEO is the highest-ranking executive in a company, making corporate decisions, managing operations, allocating resources, and serving as the main point of communication between the board of directors and the company.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In the UK, chief executive and chief executive officer are used in local government, where their position in law is described as the "head of paid service", and in business and in the charitable sector.
[src:energy-management/ceo] As of 2013, the use of the term director for senior charity staff is deprecated to avoid confusion with the legal duties and responsibilities associated with being a charity director or trustee, which are normally non-executive (unpaid) roles.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The term **managing director** is often used in lieu of chief executive officer.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Business publicists since the days of Edward Bernays (1891–1995) and his client John D.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Rockefeller (1839–1937) and even more successfully the corporate publicists for Henry Ford, promoted the concept of the "celebrity CEO".
[src:energy-management/ceo] Business journalists have often adopted this approach, which assumes that the corporate achievements, especially in the arena of manufacturing, are produced by uniquely talented individuals, especially the "heroic CEO".
[src:energy-management/ceo] In effect, journalists celebrate a CEO who takes distinctive strategic actions.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The model is the celebrity in entertainment, sports, and politics – compare the "great man theory".
[src:energy-management/ceo] Journalism thereby exaggerates the importance of the CEO and tends to neglect harder-to-describe broader corporate factors.
[src:energy-management/ceo] There is little attention to the intricately organized technical bureaucracy that actually does the work.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Hubris sets in when the CEO internalizes the celebrity and becomes excessively self-confident in making complex decisions.
[src:energy-management/ceo] There may be an emphasis on the sort of decisions that attract the celebrity journalists.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Research published in 2009 by Ulrike Malmendier and Geoffrey Tate indicates that "firms with award-winning CEOs subsequently underperform, in terms both of stock and of operating performance".
[src:energy-management/ceo] CEOs and senior executives are governed by the board of directors.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The proper selection and evaluation of the CEO and the executive team is critical to the company’s performance.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Yet there is no established standard framework to evaluate and govern the CEO performance.
[src:energy-management/ceo] One initiative proposes a standardized questionnaire used in annual CEO reviews and senior executive recruitment.
[src:energy-management/ceo] These questionnaires help guide CEO strategy and assure the shareholders that the company and its executive team are on the right track.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Every CEO and C-level executive must be able to provide specific answers to the preceding questions, readily and clearly.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Additionally, these questions can also be used as a framework for evaluating potential candidates for the succession planning and selection process.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Executive compensation has been a source of criticism following a dramatic rise in pay relative to the average worker's wage.
[src:energy-management/ceo] For example, the relative pay was 20-to-1 in 1965 in the US, but had risen to 376-to-1 by 2000.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The relative pay differs around the world, and, in some smaller countries, is still around 20-to-1.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Observers differ as to whether the rise is due to competition for talent or due to lack of control by compensation committees.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In recent years, investors have demanded more say over executive pay.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Lack of diversity amongst chief executives has also been a source of criticism.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In 2023 the number rose to 10.4% of for Women CEO's of Fortune 500 companies.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Some countries have passed laws mandating boardroom gender quotas.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In 2023 Rockefeller Foundation awarded a grant to Korn Ferry to research strategies and then action a plan to help more women to become CEO's.
[src:energy-management/ceo] There are contentious claims that a significant number of CEOs have psychopathic tendencies, often characterized by power-seeking behavior and dominance.
[src:energy-management/ceo] These individuals can often conceal their ruthlessness and antisocial behavior behind a facade of charm and eloquence.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Traits such as courage and risk-taking, generally considered desirable, are often found alongside these psychopathic tendencies.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Tara Swart, a neuroscientist at MIT Sloan School of Management, has suggested that individuals with psychopathic traits thrive in chaotic environments and are aware that others do not.
[src:energy-management/ceo] As a result, they may intentionally create chaos in the workplace.
[src:energy-management/ceo] This perspective is explored in the book *Snakes in Suits*, co-authored by Robert D.
[src:energy-management/ceo] However, Scott Lilienfeld has argued that the attention given to psychopathy in the workplace by both the media and scholars has far exceeded the available scientific evidence.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Emilia Bunea, writing in *Psychology Today*, has linked psychopathic traits in managers to workplace bullying, employee dissatisfaction, and turnover intentions.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Despite this, Bunea cautions that excessive worry about supposed psychopathic managers could discourage individuals from pursuing careers in corporations and deter employees from addressing issues with difficult bosses.
[src:energy-management/ceo] There have been several notable controversies involving famous CEOs.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Some of the most prominent controversies were a result of the MeToo Movement including Harvey Weinstein and the Weinstein Company, Steve Wynn and Wynn Resorts Ltd., and Leslie Moonves & CBS.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Elon Musk, the CEO of Tesla, Inc. and SpaceX, has been the subject of several controversies.
[src:energy-management/ceo] In 2018, Musk tweeted "[a]m considering taking Tesla private at $420.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Funding secured" in the middle of a trading day and a few weeks later, Tesla announced it would go private.
[src:energy-management/ceo] The SEC investigated Musk shortly after his tweet and charged him with securities fraud.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Musk settled the controversy and stepped down as chair of Tesla's board but remained the company's CEO.
[src:energy-management/ceo] Musk and Tesla both paid a $20 million penalty to be distributed among harmed investors.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Solar energy and wind power can replace fossil fuels at the lowest cost compared to other renewable energy options.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The availability of sunshine and wind is variable and can require electrical grid upgrades, such as using long-distance electricity transmission to group a range of power sources.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Energy storage can also be used to even out power output, and demand management can limit power use when power generation is low.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Cleanly generated electricity can usually replace fossil fuels for powering transportation, heating buildings, and running industrial processes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Certain processes are more difficult to decarbonise, such as air travel and cement production.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon capture and storage (CCS) can be an option to reduce net emissions in these circumstances, although fossil fuel power plants with CCS technology is currently a high-cost climate change mitigation strategy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Human land use changes such as agriculture and deforestation cause about 1/4th of climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These changes impact how much CO2 is absorbed by plant matter and how much organic matter decays or burns to release CO2.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These changes are part of the fast carbon cycle, whereas fossil fuels release CO2 that was buried underground as part of the slow carbon cycle.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Methane is a short-lived greenhouse gas that is produced by decaying organic matter and livestock, as well as fossil fuel extraction.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Land use changes can also impact precipitation patterns and the reflectivity of the surface of the Earth.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is possible to cut emissions from agriculture by reducing food waste, switching to a more plant-based diet (also referred to as low-carbon diet), and by improving farming processes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Various policies can encourage climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon pricing systems have been set up that either tax CO2 emissions or cap total emissions and trade emission credits.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Fossil fuel subsidies can be eliminated in favour of clean energy subsidies, and incentives offered for installing energy efficiency measures or switching to electric power sources.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The first global carbon tax has been proposed by the United Nations IMO Net-Zero Framework.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another issue is overcoming environmental objections when constructing new clean energy sources and making grid modifications.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Limiting climate change by reducing greenhouse gas emissions or removing greenhouse gases from the atmosphere could be supplemented by climate technologies such as solar radiation management (or solar geoengineering).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Complementary climate change actions, including climate activism, have a focus on political and cultural aspects.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] While climate mitigation is often cast as a burden to be distributed in some or other way, it can also be seen as an opportunity for industrial development, exports, and status seeking for countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The examples and precedents that countries set may influence other countries to follow suit.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Climate change mitigation aims to sustain ecosystems to maintain human civilisation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This requires drastic cuts in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) defines *mitigation* (of climate change) as "a human intervention to reduce emissions or enhance the sinks of greenhouse gases".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is possible to approach various mitigation measures in parallel.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is because there is no single pathway to limit global warming to 1.5 or 2 °C.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The IPCC defined carbon dioxide removal as "Anthropogenic activities removing carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere and durably storing it in geological, terrestrial, or ocean reservoirs, or in products.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Greenhouse gas emissions from human activities strengthen the greenhouse effect.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Most is carbon dioxide from burning fossil fuels: coal, oil, and natural gas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Human-caused emissions have increased atmospheric carbon dioxide by about 50% over pre-industrial levels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Emissions in the 2010s averaged a record 56 billion tons (Gt) a year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In 2016, energy for electricity, heat and transport was responsible for 73.2% of GHG emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Direct industrial processes accounted for 5.2%, waste for 3.2% and agriculture, forestry and land use for 18.4%.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Electricity generation and transport are major emitters.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The largest single source is coal-fired power stations with 20% of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Deforestation and other changes in land use also emit carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The largest sources of anthropogenic methane emissions are agriculture, and gas venting and fugitive emissions from the fossil-fuel industry.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The largest agricultural methane source is livestock.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Agricultural soils emit nitrous oxide, partly due to fertilizers.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There is now a political solution to the problem of fluorinated gases from refrigerants.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is because many countries have ratified the Kigali Amendment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon dioxide (CO2) is the dominant emitted greenhouse gas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Methane (CH4) emissions almost have the same short-term impact.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Nitrous oxide (N2O) and fluorinated gases (F-Gases) play a minor role.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Livestock and manure produce 5.8% of all greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But this depends on the time frame used to calculate the global warming potential of the respective gas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions are measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists determine their CO2 equivalents from their global warming potential (GWP).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This depends on their lifetime in the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There are widely used greenhouse gas accounting methods that convert volumes of methane, nitrous oxide and other greenhouse gases to carbon dioxide equivalents.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Estimates largely depend on the ability of oceans and land sinks to absorb these gases.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Short-lived climate pollutants (SLCPs) persist in the atmosphere for a period ranging from days to 15 years.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon dioxide can remain in the atmosphere for millennia.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Short-lived climate pollutants include methane, hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), tropospheric ozone and black carbon.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists have increased the use satellites to locate and measure greenhouse gas emissions and deforestation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Earlier, scientists largely relied on or calculated estimates of greenhouse gas emissions and governments' self-reported data.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The annual "Emissions Gap Report" by UNEP stated in 2022 that it was necessary to almost halve emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In 2022, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) released its Sixth Assessment Report on climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It warned that greenhouse gas emissions must peak before 2025 at the latest and decline 43% by 2030 to have a good chance of limiting global warming to 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Or in the words of Secretary-General of the United Nations António Guterres: "Main emitters must drastically cut emissions starting this year".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] According to a joint press release published by the German Physical society and the German meteorological society in September 2025, if the current trends will continue, global temperature can rise to 3°C above pre-industrial level by the year 2050, and by 5°C by the year 2100.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The scientists emphasised the need to urgently implement already existing solutions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Climate Action Tracker described the situation on 9 November 2021 as follows.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The global temperature will rise by 2.7 °C by the end of the century with current policies and by 2.9 °C with nationally adopted policies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The temperature will rise by 2.4 °C if countries only implement the pledges for 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The rise would be 2.1 °C with the achievement of the long-term targets too.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Full achievement of all announced targets would mean the rise in global temperature will peak at 1.9 °C and go down to 1.8 °C by the year 2100.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Experts gather information about climate pledges in the Global Climate Action Portal - Nazca.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The scientific community is checking their fulfilment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There has not been a definitive or detailed evaluation of most goals set for 2020.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But it appears the world failed to meet most or all international goals set for that year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One update came during the 2021 United Nations Climate Change Conference in Glasgow.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The group of researchers running the Climate Action Tracker looked at countries responsible for 85% of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It found that only four countries or political entities—the EU, UK, Chile and Costa Rica—have published a detailed official policy‑plan that describes the steps to realise 2030 mitigation targets.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These four polities are responsible for 6% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In 2021 the US and EU launched the Global Methane Pledge to cut methane emissions by 30% by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The UK, Argentina, Indonesia, Italy and Mexico joined the initiative.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Ghana and Iraq signalled interest in joining.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A White House summary of the meeting noted those countries represent six of the top 15 methane emitters globally.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The energy system includes the delivery and use of energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is the main emitter of carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Rapid and deep reductions in the carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gas emissions from the energy sector are necessary to limit global warming to well below 2 °C.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] IPCC recommendations include reducing fossil fuel consumption, increasing production from low- and zero carbon energy sources, and increasing use of electricity and alternative energy carriers.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Nearly all scenarios and strategies involve a major increase in the use of renewable energy in combination with increased energy efficiency measures.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It will be necessary to accelerate the deployment of renewable energy six-fold from 0.25% annual growth in 2015 to 1.5% to keep global warming under 2 °C.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The competitiveness of renewable energy is a key to a rapid deployment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In 2020, onshore wind and solar photovoltaics were the cheapest source for new bulk electricity generation in many regions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Renewables may have higher storage costs but non-renewables may have higher clean-up costs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A carbon price can increase the competitiveness of renewable energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Wind and sun can provide large amounts of low-carbon energy at competitive production costs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The IPCC estimates that these two mitigation options have the largest potential to reduce emissions before 2030 at low cost.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Solar photovoltaics (PV) has become the cheapest way to generate electricity in many regions of the world.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A 2024 review found that the global levelized cost of electricity for solar PV had fallen to between US$0.039 and 0.041 per kWh.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The growth of photovoltaics has been close to exponential.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It has about doubled every three years since the 1990s.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A different technology is concentrated solar power (CSP).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This uses mirrors or lenses to concentrate a large area of sunlight on to a receiver.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] With CSP, the energy can be stored for a few hours.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Solar water heating doubled between 2010 and 2019.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Regions in the higher northern and southern latitudes have the greatest potential for wind power.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But offshore units deliver more energy per installed capacity with less fluctuations.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In most regions, wind power generation is higher in the winter when PV output is low.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For this reason, combinations of wind and solar power lead to better-balanced systems.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Other well-established renewable energy forms include hydropower, bioenergy and geothermal energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Wind and solar power production does not consistently match demand.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] To deliver reliable electricity from variable renewable energy sources such as wind and solar, electrical power systems must be flexible.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Most electrical grids were constructed for non-intermittent energy sources such as coal-fired power plants.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The integration of larger amounts of solar and wind energy into the grid requires a change of the energy system; this is necessary to ensure that the supply of electricity matches demand.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There are various ways to make the electricity system more flexible.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In many places, wind and solar generation are complementary on a daily and a seasonal scale.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There is more wind during the night and in winter when solar energy production is low.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Linking different geographical regions through long-distance transmission lines also makes it possible to reduce variability.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is possible to shift energy demand in time.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Energy demand management and the use of smart grids make it possible to match the times when variable energy production is highest.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Sector coupling can provide further flexibility.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This involves coupling the electricity sector to the heat and mobility sector via power-to-heat-systems and electric vehicles.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Energy storage helps overcome barriers to intermittent renewable energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The most commonly used and available storage method is pumped-storage hydroelectricity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This requires locations with large differences in height and access to water.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] They typically store electricity for short periods.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This and their cost makes them impractical for the large energy storage necessary to balance inter-seasonal variations in energy production.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Some locations have implemented pumped hydro storage with capacity for multi-month usage.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Nuclear power could complement renewables for electricity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] On the other hand, environmental and security risks could outweigh the benefits.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Examples of these environmental risks being the discharge of radioactive water to nearby ecosystems, and the routine release of radioactive gases as well.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The construction of new nuclear reactors currently takes about 10 years.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is much longer than scaling up the deployment of wind and solar.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] And this timing gives rise to credit risks.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However nuclear may be much cheaper in China.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] China is building a significant number of new power plants.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] As of 2019 the cost of extending nuclear power plant lifetimes is competitive with other electricity generation technologies if long term costs for nuclear waste disposal are excluded from the calculation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There is also no sufficient financial insurance for nuclear accidents.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Switching from coal to natural gas has advantages in terms of sustainability.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For a given unit of energy produced, the life-cycle greenhouse-gas emissions of natural gas are around 40 times the emissions of wind or nuclear energy but are much less than coal.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Burning natural gas produces around half the emissions of coal when used to generate electricity and around two-thirds the emissions of coal when used to produce heat.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Natural gas combustion also produces less air pollution than coal.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, natural gas is a potent greenhouse gas in itself, and leaks during extraction and transportation can negate the advantages of switching away from coal.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The technology to curb methane leaks is widely available but it is not always used.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Switching from coal to natural gas reduces emissions in the short term and thus contributes to climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, in the long term it does not provide a path to net-zero emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Developing natural gas infrastructure risks carbon lock-in and stranded assets, where new fossil infrastructure either commits to decades of carbon emissions, or has to be written off before it makes a profit.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Reducing demand for products and services that cause greenhouse gas emissions can help in mitigating climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One is to reduce demand by behavioural and cultural changes, for example by making changes in diet, especially the decision to reduce meat consumption, an effective action individuals take to fight climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another is by reducing the demand by improving infrastructure, by building a good public transport network, for example.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Lastly, changes in end-use technology can reduce energy demand.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For instance a well-insulated house emits less than a poorly-insulated house.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Mitigation options that reduce demand for products or services help people make personal choices to reduce their carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This could be in their choice of transport or food.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] So these mitigation options have many social aspects that focus on demand reduction; they are therefore *demand-side* *mitigation actions*.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For example, people with high socio-economic status often cause more greenhouse gas emissions than those from a lower status.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] If they reduce their emissions and promote green policies, these people could become low-carbon lifestyle role models.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, there are many psychological variables that influence consumers.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These include awareness and perceived risk.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Government policies can support or hinder demand-side mitigation options.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For example, public policy can promote circular economy concepts which would support climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Reducing greenhouse gas emissions is linked to the sharing economy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There is a debate regarding the correlation of economic growth and emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It seems economic growth no longer necessarily means higher emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A 2024 article in *Nature Climate Change* emphasised the importance of integrating behavioural science into climate change mitigation strategies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Six key recommendations aimed at improving individual and collective actions toward reducing greenhouse gas emissions include overcoming barriers to research, fostering cross-disciplinary collaborations, and promoting practical behaviour-oriented solutions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These insights suggest that behavioural science plays a crucial role alongside technological and policy measures in addressing climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A paper published in *Environmental Research Letters* in 2024 described the growing role of demand-side strategies in achieving climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Global primary energy demand exceeded 161,000 terawatt hours (TWh) in 2018.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This refers to electricity, transport and heating including all losses.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In transport and electricity production, fossil fuel usage has a low efficiency of less than 50%.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Large amounts of heat in power plants and in motors of vehicles go to waste.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The actual amount of energy consumed is significantly lower at 116,000 TWh.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Energy conservation is the effort made to reduce the consumption of energy by using less of an energy service.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One way is to use energy more efficiently.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This means using less energy than before to produce the same service.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another way is to reduce the amount of service used.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] An example of this would be to drive less.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Energy conservation is at the top of the sustainable energy hierarchy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] When consumers reduce wastage and losses they can conserve energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The upgrading of technology as well as the improvements to operations and maintenance can result in overall efficiency improvements.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Efficient energy use (or *energy efficiency*) is the process of reducing the amount of energy required to provide products and services.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Improved energy efficiency in buildings ("green buildings"), industrial processes and transportation could reduce the world's energy needs in 2050 by one third.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This would help reduce global emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For example, insulating a building allows it to use less heating and cooling energy to achieve and maintain thermal comfort.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Improvements in energy efficiency are generally achieved by adopting a more efficient technology or production process.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another way is to use commonly accepted methods to reduce energy losses.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Individual action on climate change can include personal choices in many areas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These include diet, travel, household energy use, consumption of goods and services, and family size.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] People who wish to reduce their carbon footprint can take high-impact actions such as avoiding frequent flying and petrol-fuelled cars, eating mainly a plant-based diet, having fewer children, using clothes and electrical products for longer, and electrifying homes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These approaches are more practical for people in high-income countries with high-consumption lifestyles.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Naturally, it is more difficult for those with lower income statuses to make these changes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is because choices like electric-powered cars may not be available.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Excessive consumption is more to blame for climate change than population increase.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] High-consumption lifestyles have a greater environmental impact, with the richest 10% of people emitting about half the total lifestyle emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Some scientists say that avoiding meat and dairy foods is the single biggest way an individual can reduce their environmental impact.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The widespread adoption of a vegetarian diet could cut food-related greenhouse gas emissions by 63% by 2050.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] China introduced new dietary guidelines in 2016 which aim to cut meat consumption by 50% and thereby reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 1 Gt per year by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Overall, food accounts for the largest share of consumption-based greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is responsible for nearly 20% of the global carbon footprint.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Almost 15% of all anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions have been attributed to the livestock sector.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A shift towards plant-based diets would help to mitigate climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In particular, reducing meat consumption would help to reduce methane emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The Global Methane Pledge is an initiative launched by the United States and European Union to reduce global methane emissions by 30% by 2030 to keep the 1.5°C global warming limit in reach.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] If high-income nations switched to a plant-based diet, vast amounts of land used for animal agriculture could be allowed to return to their natural state.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This in turn has the potential to sequester 100 billion tonnes of CO2 by the end of the century.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A comprehensive analysis found that plant based diets reduce emissions, water pollution and land use significantly (by 75%), while reducing the destruction of wildlife and usage of water.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Population growth has resulted in higher greenhouse gas emissions in most regions, particularly Africa.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, economic growth has a bigger effect than population growth.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Rising incomes, changes in consumption and dietary patterns, as well as population growth, cause pressure on land and other natural resources.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This leads to more greenhouse gas emissions and fewer carbon sinks.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Some scholars have argued that humane policies to slow population growth should be part of a broad climate response together with policies that end fossil fuel use and encourage sustainable consumption.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Advances in female education and reproductive health, especially voluntary family planning, can contribute to reducing population growth.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] An important mitigation measure is "preserving and enhancing carbon sinks".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This refers to the management of Earth's natural carbon sinks in a way that preserves or increases their capability to remove CO2 from the atmosphere and to store it durably.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists call this process also carbon sequestration.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In the context of climate change mitigation, the IPCC defines a *sink* as "Any process, activity or mechanism which removes a greenhouse gas, an aerosol or a precursor of a greenhouse gas from the atmosphere".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Globally, the two most important carbon sinks are vegetation and the ocean.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] To enhance the ability of ecosystems to sequester carbon, changes are necessary in agriculture and forestry.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Examples are preventing deforestation and restoring natural ecosystems by reforestation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scenarios that limit global warming to 1.5 °C typically project the large-scale use of carbon dioxide removal methods over the 21st century.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There are concerns about over-reliance on these technologies, and their environmental impacts.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But ecosystem restoration and reduced conversion are among the mitigation tools that can yield the most emissions reductions before 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Land-based mitigation options are referred to as "AFOLU mitigation options" in the 2022 IPCC report on mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] A high mitigation potential is found for reducing deforestation in tropical regions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The economic potential of these activities has been estimated to be 4.2 to 7.4 gigatonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent (GtCO2 -eq) per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The Stern Review on the economics of climate change stated in 2007 that curbing deforestation was a highly cost-effective way of reducing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] About 95% of deforestation occurs in the tropics, where clearing of land for agriculture is one of the main causes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One forest conservation strategy is to transfer rights over land from public ownership to its indigenous inhabitants.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Land concessions often go to powerful extractive companies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Conservation strategies that exclude and even evict humans, called fortress conservation, often lead to more exploitation of the land.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is because the native inhabitants turn to work for extractive companies to survive.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Proforestation is promoting forests to capture their full ecological potential.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is a mitigation strategy as secondary forests that have regrown in abandoned farmland are found to have less biodiversity than the original old-growth forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Original forests store 60% more carbon than these new forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Strategies include rewilding and establishing wildlife corridors.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Afforestation is the establishment of trees where there was previously no tree cover.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scenarios for new plantations covering up to 4000 million hectares (Mha) (6300 x 6300 km) suggest cumulative carbon storage of more than 900 GtC (2300 GtCO2) until 2100.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But they are not a viable alternative to aggressive emissions reduction.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is because the plantations would need to be so large they would eliminate most natural ecosystems or reduce food production.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One example is the Trillion Tree Campaign.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, preserving biodiversity is also important and for example not all grasslands are suitable for conversion into forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Grasslands can even turn from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Reforestation is the restocking of existing depleted forests or in places where there were recently forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Reforestation could save at least 1 GtCO2 per year, at an estimated cost of $5–15 per tonne of carbon dioxide (tCO2).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Restoring all degraded forests all over the world could capture about 205 GtC (750 GtCO2).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] With increased intensive agriculture and urbanisation, there is an increase in the amount of abandoned farmland.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] By some estimates, for every acre of original old-growth forest cut down, more than 50 acres of new secondary forests are growing.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In some countries, promoting regrowth on abandoned farmland could offset years of emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Planting new trees can be expensive and a risky investment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] For example, about 80 per cent of planted trees in the Sahel die within two years.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Reforestation has higher carbon storage potential than afforestation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Even long-deforested areas still contain an "underground forest" of living roots and tree stumps.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Helping native species sprout naturally is cheaper than planting new trees and they are more likely to survive.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This could include pruning and coppicing to accelerate growth.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This also provides woodfuel, which is otherwise a major source of deforestation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Such practices, called farmer-managed natural regeneration, are centuries old but the biggest obstacle towards implementation is ownership of the trees by the state.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The state often sells timber rights to businesses which leads to locals uprooting seedlings because they see them as a liability.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Legal aid for locals and changes to property law such as in Mali and Niger have led to significant changes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists describe them as the largest positive environmental transformation in Africa.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is possible to discern from space the border between Niger and the more barren land in Nigeria, where the law has not changed.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Rangelands account for more half the world's land and could sequester 35% of terrestrial carbon.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Pastoralists are those who move with their herds that feed and migrate over often unenclosed grazelands.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Such land is usually unable to grow any other kind of food.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Rangelands coevolved with large wild herds, many of which have decreased or gone extinct, and pastoralists' herds replace such wild herds and thus help maintain the ecosystem.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, the movement of herds grazing on large areas over vast distances is increasingly restricted by governments, who often grant exclusive title to lands for more profitable uses which restricts pastoralists to more enclose spaces.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This has led to the overgrazing of the land and desertification, as well as conflict.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There are many measures to increase soil carbon.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This makes it complex and hard to measure and account for.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] One advantage is that there are fewer trade-offs for these measures than for BECCS or afforestation, for example.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Globally, protecting healthy soils and restoring the soil carbon sponge could remove 7.6 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere annually.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is more than the annual emissions of the US.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Trees capture CO2 while growing above ground and exuding larger amounts of carbon below ground.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Trees contribute to the building of a soil carbon sponge.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon formed above ground is released as CO2 immediately when wood is burned.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] If dead wood remains untouched, only some of the carbon returns to the atmosphere as decomposition proceeds.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Farming can deplete soil carbon and render soil incapable of supporting life.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, conservation farming can protect carbon in soils, and repair damage over time.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The farming practice of cover crops is a form of carbon farming.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Methods that enhance carbon sequestration in soil include no-till farming, residue mulching and crop rotation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists have described the best management practices for European soils to increase soil organic carbon.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These are conversion of arable land to grassland, straw incorporation, reduced tillage, straw incorporation combined with reduced tillage, ley cropping system and cover crops.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another mitigation option is the production of biochar and its storage in soils This is the solid material that remains after the pyrolysis of biomass.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Biochar production releases half of the carbon from the biomass—either released into the atmosphere or captured with CCS—and retains the other half in the stable biochar.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It can endure in soil for thousands of years.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Biochar may increase the soil fertility of acidic soils and increase agricultural productivity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] During production of biochar, heat is released which may be used as bioenergy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Wetland restoration is an important mitigation measure.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It has moderate to great mitigation potential on a limited land area with low trade-offs and costs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Wetlands perform two important functions in relation to climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] They can sequester carbon, converting carbon dioxide to solid plant material through photosynthesis.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Wetlands store about 45 million tonnes of carbon per year globally.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Some wetlands are a significant source of methane emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Peatland globally covers just 3% of the land's surface.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But it stores up to 550 gigatonnes (Gt) of carbon.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This represents 42% of all soil carbon and exceeds the carbon stored in all other vegetation types, including the world's forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The threat to peatlands includes draining the areas for agriculture.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Another threat is cutting down trees for lumber, as the trees help hold and fix the peatland.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Additionally, peat is often sold for compost.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It is possible to restore degraded peatlands by blocking drainage channels in the peatland, and allowing natural vegetation to recover.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Mangroves, salt marshes and seagrasses make up the majority of the ocean's vegetated habitats.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] They only equal 0.05% of the plant biomass on land.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But they store carbon 40 times faster than tropical forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Bottom trawling, dredging for coastal development and fertiliser runoff have damaged coastal habitats.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Notably, 85% of oyster reefs globally have been removed in the last two centuries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Oyster reefs clean the water and help other species thrive.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In addition, oyster reefs mitigate the effects of climate change by reducing the force of waves from hurricanes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] They also reduce the erosion from rising sea levels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Restoration of coastal wetlands is thought to be more cost-effective than restoration of inland wetlands.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These options focus on the carbon which ocean reservoirs can store.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] They include ocean fertilization, ocean alkalinity enhancement or enhanced weathering.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The IPCC found in 2022 ocean-based mitigation options currently have only limited deployment potential.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But it assessed that their future mitigation potential is large.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It found that in total, ocean-based methods could remove 1–100 Gt of CO2 per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Their costs are in the order of US$40–500 per tonne of CO2.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Most of these options could also help to reduce ocean acidification.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is the drop in pH value caused by increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The recovery of whale populations can play a role in mitigation as whales play a significant part in nutrient recycling in the ocean.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This occurs through what is referred to as the whale pump, where whales' liquid feces stay at the surface of the ocean.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Phytoplankton live near the surface of the ocean in order use sunlight to photosynthesize and rely on much of the carbon, nitrogen and iron of the feces.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] As the phytoplankton form the base of the marine food chain this increases ocean biomass and thus the amount of carbon sequestrated in it.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Blue carbon management is another type of ocean-based biological carbon dioxide removal (CDR).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It can involve land-based as well as ocean-based measures.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The term usually refers to the role that tidal marshes, mangroves and seagrasses can play in carbon sequestration.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Some of these efforts can also take place in deep ocean waters.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is where the vast majority of ocean carbon is held.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These ecosystems can contribute to climate change mitigation and also to ecosystem-based adaptation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Conversely, when blue carbon ecosystems are degraded or lost they release carbon back to the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] There is increasing interest in developing blue carbon potential.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists have found that in some cases these types of ecosystems remove far more carbon per area than terrestrial forests.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] However, the long-term effectiveness of blue carbon as a carbon dioxide removal solution remains under discussion.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Enhanced weathering could remove 2–4 Gt of CO2 per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This process aims to accelerate natural weathering by spreading finely ground silicate rock, such as basalt, onto surfaces.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This speeds up chemical reactions between rocks, water, and air.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It removes carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, permanently storing it in solid carbonate minerals or ocean alkalinity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Cost estimates are in the US$50–200 per tonne range of CO2.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] In addition to traditional land-based methods to remove carbon dioxide (CO2) from the air, other technologies are under development.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These could reduce CO2 emissions and lower existing atmospheric CO2 levels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Carbon capture and storage (CCS) is a method to mitigate climate change by capturing CO2 from large point sources, such as cement factories or biomass power plants.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It then stores it away safely instead of releasing it into the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The IPCC estimates that the costs of halting global warming would double without CCS.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Among the most viable carbon dioxide removal methods considered alongside solar radiation modification, biochar soil amendment is already being deployed commercially.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Studies indicate that the carbon it contains remains stable in soils for centuries, giving it a durable potential of removing gigatonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Expert assessments place the net cost of removing CO2 with biochar between US$30 and $120 per tonne.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Market data show that biochar supplied 94% of all durable CDR credits delivered in 2023, demonstrating current scalability.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] While models confirm that SAI would lower global mean temperature, there are potential side effect including ozone depletion, altered regional precipitation patterns, and the risk of a sudden "termination shock" warming if the programme were interrupted.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] These systemic risks are absent from biochar deployment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Bioenergy with carbon capture and storage (BECCS) expands on the potential of CCS and aims to lower atmospheric CO2 levels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This process uses biomass grown for bioenergy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The biomass yields energy in useful forms such as electricity, heat, biofuels, etc. through consumption of the biomass via combustion, fermentation, or pyrolysis.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The process captures the CO2 that was extracted from the atmosphere when it grew.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It then stores it underground or via land application as biochar.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This effectively removes it from the atmosphere.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This makes BECCS a negative emissions technology (NET).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Scientists estimated the potential range of negative emissions from BECCS in 2018 as 0–22 Gt per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] As of 2022, BECCS was capturing approximately 2 million tonnes per year of CO2 annually.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] The cost and availability of biomass limits wide deployment of BECCS.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] BECCS currently forms a big part of achieving climate targets beyond 2050 in modelling, such as by the Integrated Assessment Models (IAMs) associated with the IPCC process.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] But many scientists are sceptical due to the risk of loss of biodiversity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Direct air capture is a process of capturing CO2 directly from the ambient air.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] This is in contrast to CCS which captures carbon from point sources.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] It generates a concentrated stream of CO2 for sequestration, utilisation or production of carbon-neutral fuel and windgas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p01] Artificial processes vary, and there are concerns about the long-term effects of some of these processes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Taking into account direct and indirect emissions, industry is the sector with the highest share of global emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] 2016 global greenhouse gas emissions by sector.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The building sector accounts for 23% of global energy-related CO2 emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] About half of the energy is used for space and water heating.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Building insulation can reduce the primary energy demand significantly.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Heat pump loads may also provide a flexible resource that can participate in demand response to integrate variable renewable resources into the grid.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Solar water heating uses thermal energy directly.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Sufficiency measures include moving to smaller houses when the needs of households change, mixed use of spaces and the collective use of devices.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Planners and civil engineers can construct new buildings using passive solar building design, low-energy building, or zero-energy building techniques.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In addition, it is possible to design buildings that are more energy-efficient to cool by using lighter-coloured, more reflective materials in the development of urban areas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Heat pumps efficiently heat buildings, and cool them by air conditioning.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A modern heat pump typically transports around three to five times more thermal energy than electrical energy consumed.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The amount depends on the coefficient of performance and the outside temperature.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Refrigeration and air conditioning account for about 10% of global CO2 emissions caused by fossil fuel-based energy production and the use of fluorinated gases.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Alternative cooling systems, such as passive cooling building design and passive daytime radiative cooling surfaces, can reduce air conditioning use.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Suburbs and cities in hot and arid climates can significantly reduce energy consumption from cooling with daytime radiative cooling.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Energy consumption for cooling is likely to rise significantly due to increasing heat and availability of devices in poorer countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Of the 2.8 billion people living in the hottest parts of the world, only 8% currently have air conditioners, compared with 90% of people in the US and Japan.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Adoption of air conditioners typically increases in warmer areas at above $10,000 annual household income.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] By combining energy efficiency improvements and decarbonising electricity for air conditioning with the transition away from super-polluting refrigerants, the world could avoid cumulative greenhouse gas emissions of up to 210–460 GtCO2-eq over the next four decades.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A shift to renewable energy in the cooling sector comes with two advantages: Solar energy production with mid-day peaks corresponds with the load required for cooling and additionally, cooling has a large potential for load management in the electric grid.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Cities emitted 28 GtCO2-eq in 2020 of combined CO2 and CH4 emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This was from producing and consuming goods and services.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Climate-smart urban planning aims to reduce sprawl to reduce the distance travelled.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This lowers emissions from transportation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Switching from cars by improving walkability and cycling infrastructure is beneficial to a country's economy as a whole.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Urban forestry, lakes and other blue and green infrastructure can reduce emissions directly and indirectly by reducing energy demand for cooling.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Methane emissions from municipal solid waste can be reduced by segregation, composting, and recycling.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Transportation accounts for 15% of emissions worldwide.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Increasing the use of public transport, low-carbon freight transport and cycling are important components of transport decarbonisation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Electric vehicles and environmentally friendly rail help to reduce the consumption of fossil fuels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In most cases, electric trains are more efficient than air transport and truck transport.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Other efficiency means include improved public transport, smart mobility, carsharing and electric hybrids.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Fossil-fuel for passenger cars can be included in emissions trading.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Furthermore, moving away from a car-dominated transport system towards low-carbon advanced public transport system is important.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Heavyweight, large personal vehicles (such as cars) require a lot of energy to move and take up much urban space.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Several alternatives modes of transport are available to replace these.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The European Union has made smart mobility part of its European Green Deal.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In smart cities, smart mobility is also important.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The World Bank is helping lower income countries buy electric buses.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Their purchase price is higher than diesel buses.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But lower running costs and health improvements due to cleaner air can offset this higher price.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Between one quarter and three quarters of cars on the road by 2050 are forecast to be electric vehicles.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Hydrogen may be a solution for long-distance heavy freight trucks, if batteries alone are too heavy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the shipping industry, the use of liquefied natural gas (LNG) as a marine bunker fuel is driven by emissions regulations.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Ship operators must switch from heavy fuel oil to more expensive oil-based fuels, implement costly flue gas treatment technologies or switch to LNG engines.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Methane slip, when gas leaks unburned through the engine, lowers the advantages of LNG.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Maersk, the world's biggest container shipping line and vessel operator, warns of stranded assets when investing in transitional fuels like LNG.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The company lists green ammonia as one of the preferred fuel types of the future.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] It has announced the first carbon-neutral vessel on the water by 2023, running on carbon-neutral methanol.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Cruise operators are trialling partially hydrogen-powered ships.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Hybrid and all electric ferries are suitable for short distances.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Norway's goal is an all electric fleet by 2025.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.3–1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of all CO2 emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The aviation industry has become more fuel efficient.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] It is possible to reduce aviation's environmental footprint by better fuel economy in aircraft.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Optimising flight routes to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from nitrogen oxides, particulates or contrails can also help.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Aviation biofuel, carbon emission trading and carbon offsetting, part of the 191 nation ICAO's Carbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International Aviation (CORSIA), can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and taxation on flights can lead to fewer flights.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or hydrogen-powered aircraft may replace fossil fuel-powered aircraft.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Experts expect emissions from aviation to rise in most projections, at least until 2040.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] They currently amount to 180 Mt of CO2 or 11% of transport emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Aviation biofuel and hydrogen can only cover a small proportion of flights in the coming years.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Experts expect hybrid-driven aircraft to start commercial regional scheduled flights after 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Battery-powered aircraft are likely to enter the market after 2035.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Under CORSIA, flight operators can purchase carbon offsets to cover their emissions above 2019 levels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Almost 20% of greenhouse gas emissions come from the agriculture and forestry sector.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] To significantly reduce these emissions, annual investments in the agriculture sector need to increase to $260 billion by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The potential benefits from these investments are estimated at $4.3 trillion by 2030, offering a substantial economic return of 16-to-1.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation measures in the food system can be divided into four categories.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] These are demand-side changes, ecosystem protections, mitigation on farms, and mitigation in supply chains.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] On the demand side, limiting food waste is an effective way to reduce food emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Changes to a diet less reliant on animal products such as plant-based diets are also effective.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] With 21% of global methane emissions, cattle are a major driver of global warming.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] When rainforests are cut and the land is converted for grazing, the impact is even higher.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In Brazil, producing 1 kg of beef can result in the emission of up to 335 kg CO2-eq.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Increasing the milk yield of dairy cows has been shown to reduce emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Other livestock, manure management and rice cultivation also emit greenhouse gases, in addition to fossil fuel combustion in agriculture.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Important mitigation options for reducing the greenhouse gas emissions from livestock include genetic selection, introduction of methanotrophic bacteria into the rumen, vaccines, feeds, diet modification and grazing management.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Other options are diet changes towards ruminant-free alternatives, such as milk substitutes and meat analogues.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Non-ruminant livestock, such as poultry, emit far fewer GHGs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] It is possible to cut methane emissions in rice cultivation by improved water management, combining dry seeding and one drawdown, or executing a sequence of wetting and drying.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This results in emission reductions of up to 90% compared to full flooding and even increased yields.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Reducing the usage of nitrogen fertilizers through nutrient management could avoid nitrous oxide emissions equal to 2.77 - 11.48 gigatons of carbon dioxide from 2020 to 2050.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Industry is the largest emitter of greenhouse gases when direct and indirect emissions are included.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Electrification can reduce emissions from industry.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Green hydrogen can play a major role in energy-intensive industries for which electricity is not an option.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Further mitigation options involve the steel and cement industry, which can switch to a less polluting production process.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Products can be made with less material to reduce emission-intensity and industrial processes can be made more efficient.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Finally, circular economy measures reduce the need for new materials.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This also saves on emissions that would have been released from the mining of collecting of those materials.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The decarbonisation of cement production requires new technologies, and therefore investment in innovation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Bioconcrete is one possibility to reduce emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But no technology for mitigation is yet mature.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] So CCS will be necessary at least in the short-term.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Another sector with a significant carbon footprint is the steel sector, which is responsible for about 7% of global emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Emissions can be reduced by using electric arc furnaces to melt and recycle scrap steel.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] To produce virgin steel without emissions, blast furnaces could be replaced by hydrogen direct reduced iron and electric arc furnaces.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Alternatively, carbon capture and storage solutions can be used.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Coal, gas and oil production often come with significant methane leakage.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the early 2020s some governments recognised the scale of the problem and introduced regulations.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Methane leaks at oil and gas wells and processing plants are cost-effective to fix in countries which can easily trade gas internationally.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] There are leaks in countries where gas is cheap; such as Iran, Russia, and Turkmenistan.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Nearly all this can be stopped by replacing old components and preventing routine flaring.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Coalbed methane may continue leaking even after the mine has been closed.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But it can be captured by drainage and/or ventilation systems.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Fossil fuel firms do not always have financial incentives to tackle methane leakage.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Co-benefits of climate change mitigation, also often referred to as *ancillary benefits*, were firstly dominated in the scientific literature by studies that describe how lower GHG emissions lead to better air quality and consequently impact human health positively.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The scope of co-benefits research expanded to its economic, social, ecological and political implications.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Positive secondary effects that occur from climate mitigation and adaptation measures have been mentioned in research since the 1990s.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The IPCC first mentioned the role of co-benefits in 2001, followed by its fourth and fifth assessment cycle stressing improved working environment, reduced waste, health benefits and reduced capital expenditures.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the early 2000s the OECD was further fostering its efforts in promoting ancillary benefits.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The IPCC pointed out in 2007: "Co-benefits of GHG mitigation can be an important decision criteria in analyses carried out by policy-makers, but they are often neglected" and added that the co-benefits are "not quantified, monetised or even identified by businesses and decision-makers".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Appropriate consideration of co-benefits can greatly "influence policy decisions concerning the timing and level of mitigation action", and there can be "significant advantages to the national economy and technical innovation".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] An analysis of climate action in the UK found that public health benefits are a major component of the total benefits derived from climate action.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Co-benefits can positively impact employment, industrial development, states' energy independence and energy self-consumption.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The deployment of renewable energies can foster job opportunities.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Depending on the country and deployment scenario, replacing coal power plants with renewable energy can more than double the number of jobs per average MW capacity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Investments in renewable energies, especially in solar- and wind energy, can boost the value of production.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Countries which rely on energy imports can enhance their energy independence and ensure supply security by deploying renewables.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] National energy generation from renewables lowers the demand for fossil fuel imports which scales up annual economic saving.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The European Commission forecasts a shortage of 180,000 skilled workers in hydrogen production and 66,000 in solar photovoltaic power by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A higher share of renewables can additionally lead to more energy security.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Socioeconomic co-benefits have been analysed such as energy access in rural areas and improved rural livelihoods.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Rural areas which are not fully electrified can benefit from the deployment of renewable energies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Solar-powered mini-grids can remain economically viable, cost-competitive and reduce the number of power cuts.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Energy reliability has additional social implications: stable electricity improves the quality of education.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The International Energy Agency (IEA) spelled out the "multiple benefits approach" of energy efficiency while the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) operationalised the list of co-benefits of the renewable energy sector.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The health benefits from climate change mitigation are significant.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Potential measures can not only mitigate future health impacts from climate change but also improve health directly.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Climate change mitigation is interconnected with various health co-benefits, such as those from reduced air pollution.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Air pollution generated by fossil fuel combustion is both a major driver of global warming and the cause of a large number of annual deaths.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Some estimates are as high as 8.7 million excess deaths during 2018.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A 2023 study estimated that fossil fuels kill over 5 million people each year, as of 2019, by causing diseases such as heart attack, stroke and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Particulate air pollution kills by far the most, followed by ground-level ozone.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation policies can also promote healthier diets such as less red meat, more active lifestyles, and increased exposure to green urban spaces.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Access to urban green spaces provides benefits to mental health as well.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The increased use of green and blue infrastructure can reduce the urban heat island effect.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Some mitigation measures have co-benefits in the area of climate change adaptation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This is for example the case for many nature-based solutions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Examples in the urban context include urban green and blue infrastructure which provide mitigation as well as adaptation benefits.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This can be in the form of urban forests and street trees, green roofs and walls, urban agriculture and so forth.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The mitigation is achieved through the conservation and expansion of carbon sinks and reduced energy use of buildings.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Adaptation benefits come for example through reduced heat stress and flooding risk.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation measures can also have negative side effects and risks.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In agriculture and forestry, mitigation measures can affect biodiversity and ecosystem functioning.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In renewable energy, mining for metals and minerals can increase threats to conservation areas.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] There is some research into ways to recycle solar panels and electronic waste.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This would create a source for materials so there is no need to mine them.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Scholars have found that discussions about risks and negative side effects of mitigation measures can lead to deadlock or the feeling that there are insuperable barriers to taking action.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This deadlock or feelings often happens because people focus more on possible losses than benefits, making them hesitant to support change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Uncertainty also plays a role, as decision-makers may overthink worst-case scenarios and delay action instead of moving forward.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In addition, strong disagreements between groups and the lack of a shared way to judge risks can make compromise difficult, leading to political gridlock.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Several factors affect mitigation cost estimates.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This is a reference scenario that the alternative mitigation scenario is compared with.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Others are the way costs are modelled, and assumptions about future government policy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Cost estimates for mitigation for specific regions depend on the quantity of emissions allowed for that region in future, as well as the timing of interventions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation costs will vary according to how and when emissions are cut.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Early, well-planned action will minimise the costs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Globally, the benefits of keeping warming under 2 °C exceed the costs, which according to The Economist are affordable.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Economists estimate the cost of climate change mitigation at between 1% and 2% of GDP.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] While this is a large sum, it is still far less than the subsidies governments provide to the fossil fuel industry.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The International Monetary Fund estimated this at more than $5 trillion per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Another estimate says that financial flows for climate mitigation and adaptation are going to be over $800 billion per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] These financial requirements are predicted to exceed $4 trillion per year by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Globally, limiting warming to 2 °C may result in higher economic benefits than economic costs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The economic repercussions of mitigation vary widely across regions and households, depending on policy design and level of international cooperation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Delayed global cooperation increases policy costs across regions, especially in those that are relatively carbon intensive at present.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Pathways with uniform carbon values show higher mitigation costs in more carbon-intensive regions, in fossil-fuels exporting regions and in poorer regions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Aggregate quantifications expressed in GDP or monetary terms undervalue the economic effects on households in poorer countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The actual effects on welfare and well-being are comparatively larger.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Cost–benefit analysis may be unsuitable for analysing climate change mitigation as a whole.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But it is still useful for analysing the difference between a 1.5 °C target and 2 °C.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] One way of estimating the cost of reducing emissions is by considering the likely costs of potential technological and output changes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Policymakers can compare the marginal abatement costs of different methods to assess the cost and amount of possible abatement over time.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The marginal abatement costs of the various measures will differ by country, by sector, and over time.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Eco-tariffs on only imports contribute to reduced global export competitiveness and to deindustrialisation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] It is possible to avoid some of the costs of the effects of climate change by limiting climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] According to the Stern Review, inaction can be as high as the equivalent of losing at least 5% of global gross domestic product (GDP) each year, now and forever.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This can be up to 20% of GDP or more when including a wider range of risks and impacts.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But mitigating climate change will only cost about 2% of GDP.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Also it may not be a good idea from a financial perspective to delay significant reductions in greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation solutions are often evaluated in terms of costs and greenhouse gas reduction potentials.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This fails to take into account the direct effects on human well-being.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Mitigation at the speed and scale required to limit warming to 2 °C or below implies deep economic and structural changes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] These raise multiple types of distributional concerns across regions, income classes and sectors.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] There have been different proposals on how to allocate responsibility for cutting emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] These include egalitarianism, basic needs according to a minimum level of consumption, proportionality and the polluter-pays principle.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A specific proposal is "equal per capita entitlements".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the first category, emissions are allocated according to national population.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the second category, emissions are allocated in a way that attempts to account for historical or cumulative emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In order to reconcile economic development with mitigating carbon emissions, developing countries need particular support.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This would be both financial and technical.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The IPCC found that accelerated support would also tackle inequities in financial and economic vulnerability to climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] One way to achieve this is the Kyoto Protocol's Clean Development Mechanism (CDM).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Climate change mitigation policies can have a large and complex impact on the socio-economic status of individuals and countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] It is important to design policies well and make them inclusive.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Otherwise climate change mitigation measures can impose higher financial costs on poor households.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Current climate policies contribute to some changes but remain far from accelerating low-carbon transitions beyond historical trends and to levels consistent with Paris climate targets, and would still result in global warming of about 2.7 °C by 2100.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In order to identify relatively more effective policies, an evaluation was conducted on 1,500 climate policy interventions made between 1998 and 2022.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The interventions took place in 41 countries and across 6 continents, which together contributed 81% of the world's total emissions as of 2019.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The evaluation found 63 successful interventions that resulted in significant emission reductions; the total CO2 release averted by these interventions was between 0.6 and 1.8 billion metric tonnes.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The study focused on interventions with at least 4.5% emission reductions, but the researchers noted that meeting the reductions required by the Paris Agreement would require 23 billion metric tonnes per year.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Generally, carbon pricing was found to be most effective in developed countries, while regulation was most effective in the developing countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Complementary policy mixes benefited from synergies, and were mostly found to be more effective interventions than the implementation of isolated policies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The OECD recognise 48 distinct climate mitigation policies suitable for implementation at national level.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Broadly, these can be categorised into three types: *market based* instruments, *non market based* instruments and *other* policies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Imposing additional costs on greenhouse gas emissions can make fossil fuels less competitive and accelerate investments into low-carbon sources of energy.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] A growing number of countries raise a fixed carbon tax or participate in dynamic carbon emission trading (ETS) systems.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2021, more than 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions were covered by a carbon price.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This was a big increase from earlier due to the introduction of the Chinese national carbon trading scheme.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Trading schemes offer the possibility to limit emission allowances to certain reduction targets.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] However, an oversupply of allowances keeps most ETS at low price levels around $10 with a low impact.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This includes the Chinese ETS which started with $7/tCO2 in 2021.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] One exception is the European Union Emission Trading Scheme where prices began to rise in 2018.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This results in additional costs of about €0.04/KWh for coal and €0.02/KWh for gas combustion for electricity, depending on the emission intensity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Industries which have high energy requirements and high emissions often pay only very low energy taxes, or even none at all.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] While this is often part of national schemes, carbon offsets and credits can be part of a voluntary market as well such as on the international market.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Notably, the company Blue Carbon of the UAE has bought ownership over an area equivalent to the United Kingdom to be preserved in return for carbon credits.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] International cooperation is considered a *critical enabler* for climate action while conflicts generally hamper it.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Almost all countries are parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The ultimate objective of the UNFCCC is to stabilise atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases at a level that would prevent dangerous human interference with the climate system.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Although not designed for this purpose, the Montreal Protocol has benefited climate change mitigation efforts.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Montreal Protocol is an international treaty that has successfully reduced emissions of ozone-depleting substances such as CFCs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] While international climate efforts have traditionally focused on demand-side policies like carbon taxes and emissions trading, a growing body of research explores supply-side treaties aimed at reducing the global output of fossil fuels.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Proponents argue these treaties may be more cost-efficient and easier to monitor than demand-side agreements, potentially addressing issues like 'carbon leakage' and the 'green paradox'.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] However, scholars note that because most major emitters are also major producers, supply-side treaties face similar challenges in participation and distributive conflict.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Historically efforts to deal with climate change have taken place at a multinational level.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] They involve attempts to reach a consensus decision at the United Nations, under the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This is the dominant approach historically of engaging as many international governments as possible in taking action on a worldwide public issue.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Montreal Protocol in 1987 is a precedent that this approach can work.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] But some critics say the top-down framework of only utilising the UNFCCC consensus approach is ineffective.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] They put forward counter-proposals of bottom-up governance.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] At this same time this would lessen the emphasis on the UNFCCC.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Kyoto Protocol to the UNFCCC adopted in 1997 set out legally binding emission reduction commitments for the "Annex 1" countries.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Protocol defined three international policy instruments ("Flexibility Mechanisms") which could be used by the Annex 1 countries to meet their emission reduction commitments.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] According to Bashmakov, use of these instruments could significantly reduce the costs for Annex 1 countries in meeting their emission reduction commitments.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Paris Agreement reached in 2015 succeeded the Kyoto Protocol which expired in 2020.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Countries that ratified the Kyoto protocol committed to reduce their emissions of carbon dioxide and five other greenhouse gases, or engage in carbon emissions trading if they maintain or increase emissions of these gases.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2015, the UNFCCC's "structured expert dialogue" came to the conclusion that, "in some regions and vulnerable ecosystems, high risks are projected even for warming above 1.5 °C".
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Together with the strong diplomatic voice of the poorest countries and the island nations in the Pacific, this expert finding was the driving force leading to the decision of the 2015 Paris Climate Conference to lay down this 1.5 °C long-term target on top of the existing 2 °C goal.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] There are individual, institutional and market barriers to achieving climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] They differ for all the different mitigation options, regions and societies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Difficulties with accounting for carbon dioxide removal can act as economic barriers.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This would apply to BECCS (bioenergy with carbon capture and storage).
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] For land-based mitigation options, finance is a major barrier.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Other barriers are cultural values, governance, accountability and institutional capacity.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] One study estimates that only 0.12% of all funding for climate-related research goes on the social science of climate change mitigation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Vastly more funding goes on natural science studies of climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Considerable sums also go on studies of the impact of climate change and adaptation to it.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] More than 1000 organisations with investments worth US$8 trillion have made commitments to fossil fuel divestment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Socially responsible investing funds allow investors to invest in funds that meet high environmental, social and corporate governance (ESG) standards.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led some governments to shift their focus away from climate action, at least temporarily.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This obstacle to environmental policy efforts may have contributed to slowed investment in green energy technologies.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The economic slowdown resulting from COVID-19 added to this effect.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2020, carbon dioxide emissions fell by 6.4% or 2.3 billion tonnes globally.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Greenhouse gas emissions rebounded later in the pandemic as many countries began lifting restrictions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The direct impact of pandemic policies had a negligible long-term impact on climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] per person, though the rate of increase diminishes with average GDP/pp of about $10,000.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The examples and precedents that countries et may influence other countries to follow suit.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The United States government has held shifting attitudes toward addressing greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Bush administration opted not to sign the Kyoto Protocol, but the Obama administration entered the Paris Agreement.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Trump administration withdrew from the Paris Agreement while increasing the export of crude oil and gas, making the United States the largest producer.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2021, the Biden administration committed to reducing emissions to half of 2005 levels by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In 2022, President Biden signed the Inflation Reduction Act into law, which is estimated to provide around $375 billion over 10 years to fight climate change.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] As of 2022 the social cost of carbon is 51 dollars a tonne whereas academics say it should be more than three times higher.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] China has committed to peak emissions by 2030 and reach net zero by 2060.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Warming cannot be limited to 1.5 °C if any coal plants in China (without carbon capture) operate after 2045.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The Chinese national carbon trading scheme started in 2021.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The European Commission estimates that an additional €477 million in annual investment is needed for the European Union to meet its Fit-for-55 decarbonisation goals.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] In the European Union, government-driven policies and the European Green Deal have helped position greentech (as an example) as a vital area for venture capital investment.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] By 2023, venture capital in the EU's greentech sector equalled that of the United States, reflecting a concerted effort to drive innovation and mitigate climate change through targeted financial support.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The European Green Deal has fostered policies that contributed to a 30% rise in venture capital for greentech companies in the EU from 2021 to 2023, despite a downturn in other sectors during the same period.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] While overall venture capital investment in the EU remains about six times lower than in the United States, the greentech sector has closed this gap significantly, attracting substantial funding.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Key areas benefitting from increased investments are energy storage, circular economy initiatives, and agricultural technology.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] This is supported by the EU's ambitious goal to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by at least 55% by 2030.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] While solar radiation modification (SRM) could reduce surface temperatures, it temporarily masks climate change rather than addressing the root cause, which is greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] SRM would work by altering how much solar radiation the Earth absorbs.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Examples include reducing the amount of sunlight reaching the surface, reducing the optical thickness and lifetime of clouds, and changing the ability of the surface to reflect radiation.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The IPCC describes SRM as a climate risk reduction strategy or supplementary option rather than a climate mitigation option.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] The terminology in this area is still evolving.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] Experts sometimes use the term *geoengineering* or climate engineering in the scientific literature for both CDR or SRM, if the techniques are used at a global scale.
[src:energy-management/climate-protection-p02] IPCC reports no longer use the terms *geoengineering* or *climate engineering*.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizational culture influences how people interact, how decisions are made (or avoided), the context within which cultural artifacts are created, employee attachment, the organization's competitive advantage, and the internal alignment of its units.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] It is distinct from the national culture or the broader cultural background of its workforce.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] A related topic, organizational identity, refers to statements and images that are important to an organization and help to differentiate it from other organizations.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] An organization may also have its own management philosophy.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizational identity influences all stakeholders, leaders and employees alike.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Various definitions exist, without consensus.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Lesley Willcoxson and Bruce Millett note that organizational cultures can be described in similar ways to wider forms of culture, such as national culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Elliott Jaques introduced the concept in his 1951 book *The Changing Culture of a Factory*.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The book was a published report of "a case study of developments in the social life of one industrial community between April 1948 and November 1950".
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The case involved a publicly-held British company engaged principally in the manufacture, sale, and servicing of metal bearings.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The study concerned itself with the description, analysis, and development of corporate group behaviors.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Researchers have proposed various dimensions individually and in combination as useful for analyzing organizational culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Examples include external/internal, strong/weak, flexible/rigid, and many others.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Culture can be externally focused, aiming to satisfy customers, investors, and partners.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Alternatively, they can be internally focused, aiming to satisfy employees, comply with union-imposed rules, or meet conduct standards around issues such as diversity, equity, and inclusion.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Many organizations lie between such extremes, attempting to balance the needs of multiple stakeholders.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Any type of culture can be strongly or only tacitly supported.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] A strong culture is characterized by reinforcing tools such as ceremonies and policies to instill and spread it.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The intent is to secure group compliance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Researchers generally report that organizations with strong cultures are more successful.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] An employee's perception of the organization's culture can have an impact on the employee's longevity with the organization.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] When organizations create a positive environment for their employees, they experience professional fulfillment, boosted performance, and a longer stint with the organization.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Quiet quitting is a principle that could potentially affect organizations with negative culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] It is the idea of doing the bare minimum on a job and setting boundaries in response to poor culture, burnout, lack of recognition, and inadequate work-life balance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] This occurs in unhealthy work environments where personal circumstances force employees to stay.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizational culture is used to control, coordinate, and integrate distinct groups across the organization.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Differences in national cultures must be addressed.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Such differences include organizational structure and manager/employee relationships.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Groupthink can lead to a lack of creativity and decisions made without critical evaluation.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Hogg and separately Deanne *et al*. stated that groupthink can occur, for example, when group members rely heavily on a charismatic figure or when members evince an "evangelical" belief in the organization's values.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Groupthink can also occur in groups characterized by a friendly climate conducive to conflict avoidance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Since the late 1960s, the so-called "Five Monkeys Experiment", which serves to exemplify the adverse effects of unquestioned traditions, has become part of management lore, often titled "How Company Policy Is Made".
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] It imagines a situation where five monkeys are in a cage with a banana tied to the ceiling.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Whenever a monkey climbs to reach the banana, all five are sprayed with cold water.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The group quickly learn to ignore the banana and punish any monkey who attempts to reach for it.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] If one monkey is removed from the cage and replaced with a newcomer, they too are punished for reaching for the banana.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] If every monkey is subsequently replaced in this manner, so that none present remember being sprayed with cold water, the group will supposedly continue to punish any attempts to reach the banana.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The monkeys are perpetuating a caution that may be redundant, "because that's the way it's always been around here".
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Willcoxson and Millett note that organizational cultures change over time.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Kotter and Heskett define an adaptive culture as characterized by managers who pay close attention to their constituencies, especially customers, initiating change when needed, and taking risks.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] They claim that organizations with adaptive cultures perform better.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Bullying manifests in workplaces that allow employees of higher status to harass those of lower status.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] This generally requires support or at least forbearance from company leaders.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Bullying can cascade down the organizational hierarchy as supervisors experiencing bullying display the same behavior to their subordinates.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Workplace bullying impacts employees, leading to increased stress on the job, decreased productivity and high turnover rates.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Employees who are bullied often remain silent because management fails to hold perpetrators accountable.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The pandemic led many organizations to incorporate limiting spread into their cultures as a collective responsibility.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Responses focused on requiring vaccines, hygiene, and masking.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] In Asia, mask-wearing was part of several national cultures predating the pandemic.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] This was driven by experience with prior flus in Asia, such as Spanish flu, Hong Kong flu, Avian flu, and Swine flu, in addition to SARS, as well as various affronts to air quality such as volcanic eruptions.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Somers categorized cultures based on whether the needs of the individual or the group were foremost.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] He used behaviors such as mask-wearing to measure collectivism vs individualism.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Cultures otherwise rated "strong" were relatively resistant to change during the pandemic.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] However, strong cultures that emphasized innovation were more willing to change.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Mandated interventions could be seen by members either as attempts to protect them or as attempts to exert control despite limited effectiveness, depending on how they were presented.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Digital tools such as videoconferencing, screen-sharing, file sharing, shared document authoring, digital whiteboards, and chat groups became widely accepted, replacing in-person meetings.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The reduced amount of face-to-face communications may have impacted organizational cultures.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] New members, lacking face time with others, experienced difficulty in adapting to their organization's culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The loss of face time affected existing employees as well, directly weakening cultures, in addition to the indirect effects that strengthened or weakened cultures as organizations reacted in various ways to the pandemic.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Some members felt disengaged and expendable rather than essential, alienated, and exhausted.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Sull and Sull reported that employees rated their leadership higher, given honest/open communication, integrity, and transparency, more than in preceding years.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Also, employers and leaders giving more attention to employees' welfare had a positive impact on cultural adherence.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Chambers claimed that this was a short-term response rather than a culture change.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Deloitte argued that employees displayed a greater sense of purpose, inspiration, and contribution.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Also, leaders became more tolerant of employees' failure because of a significant increase in experimentation and risk-taking.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Daum and Maraist claimed that a sense of purpose relates to customers and the society in which employees are part.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] They compared hospitals and retail shops.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The former had a greater sense of purpose during the pandemic, while the latter had less.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Healthy cultures address members' concerns about the well-being of the organization.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Whistleblowing, particularly when it damages a company's reputation, is considered to be a sign of a dysfunctional corporate culture, indicating that internal methods of addressing problems are inadequate.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Numerous outcomes have been associated either directly or indirectly with organizational culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The relationships between organizational culture and various outcomes include organizational performance, employee commitment, and innovation.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] A Harvard Business School study reported that culture has a significant effect on an organization's long-term economic performance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The study examined the management practices at 160 organizations over ten years and found that culture can impact performance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Performance-oriented cultures experienced better financial results.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Additionally, a 2002 Corporate Leadership Council study found that cultural traits such as risk-taking, internal communications, and flexibility are important drivers of performance.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Furthermore, innovativeness, productivity through people, and other cultural factors cited by Peters and Waterman in *In Search of Excellence* also have positive economic consequences.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Denison, Haaland, and Goelzer reported that culture contributes to the success of the organization, but not all dimensions contribute equally.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Effects differed across nations, implying that organizational culture is rooted in national culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Cultures are not static and can evolve over time, either organically or through intentional change efforts by management.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Culture change may be attempted to reduce member turnover, influence behavior, make improvements to the organization, reset objectives, rescale the organization, or achieve specific results.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizational cultures have been reported to change in stages.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Existing culture can hinder change efforts, especially where members understand the roles that they are supposed to play.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Marquis *et al.* claimed that 70% of all change efforts fail because of the members.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizational culture, and the structures in which they are embedded, often exhibit substantial inertia.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Change methodologies include Peter Senge's concept of a "learning organization" expressed in *The Fifth Discipline* or *Directive Communication's* "corporate culture evolution".
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Prior to introducing a cultural change, a needs assessment can characterize the existing culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] This involves some mixture of employee surveys, interviews, focus groups, observation, customer surveys, and other internal research.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The company must then describe the new, desired culture, and design a change process.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Cummings and Worley offer six guidelines for cultural change, in line with the eight distinct stages mentioned by Kotter.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Criticism of "organizational culture" began in the early 1980s.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Most criticism comes from writers in critical management studies who, for example, express skepticism about functionalist and unitarist views.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] They stress how these assumptions can stifle dissent and reproduce propaganda and ideology.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] They suggest that organizations do not embody a single culture (diversity), and cultural engineering may not reflect the interests of all stakeholders.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Parker suggested that many of the assumptions surrounding organizational culture are not new.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] They reflect a long-standing tension between cultural and structural (or informal and formal) versions of organizations.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Further, it is reasonable to suggest that complex organizations might have many cultures, and that such subcultures might overlap and contradict each other.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] The neat typologies of cultural forms found in textbooks rarely acknowledge such complexities, or the various economic contradictions that exist in capitalist organizations.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Smircich criticized theories that attempt to categorize or 'pigeonhole' organizational culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] She applied the metaphor of a plant root to represent culture, saying that it drives organizations rather than vice versa.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Organizations are the product of their organizational culture, which shapes behavior and interaction.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] While Schein's underlying assumptions are that beliefs, perceptions, thoughts, and feelings are taken for granted and can be observed and considered the ultimate source of values and action.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] However, such assumptions undermine attempts to categorize and define organizational culture.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] This was the largest fine in the history of this agency.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Groups within the organization may act according to their own subcultures that are not fully aligned with those of the organization as a whole.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] For example, computer technicians will have expertise, language and behaviors gained independently of the organization, but their presence can influence the culture of the larger organization.
[src:energy-management/corporate-culture] Tate describes the shadow side as the "often disagreeable, messy, crazy and opaque aspects of [an] organisation's personality".
[src:energy-management/decision-making] In psychology, **decision-making** (also spelled **decision making** and **decisionmaking**) is regarded as the cognitive process resulting in the selection of a belief or a course of action among several possible alternative options.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] It could be either rational or irrational.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] The decision-making process is a reasoning process based on assumptions of values, preferences and beliefs of the decision-maker.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Every decision-making process produces a final choice, which may or may not prompt action.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Research about decision-making is also published under the label problem solving, particularly in European psychological research.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Decision-making can be regarded as a problem-solving activity yielding a solution deemed to be optimal, or at least satisfactory.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] It is therefore a process which can be more or less rational or irrational and can be based on explicit or tacit knowledge and beliefs.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Tacit knowledge is often used to fill the gaps in complex decision-making processes.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Usually, both of these types of knowledge, tacit and explicit, are used together in the decision-making process.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] A major part of decision-making involves the analysis of a finite set of alternatives described in terms of evaluative criteria.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Then the task might be to rank these alternatives in terms of how attractive they are to the decision-maker(s) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Another task might be to find the best alternative or to determine the relative total priority of each alternative (for instance, if alternatives represent projects competing for funds) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Solving such problems is the focus of multiple-criteria decision analysis (MCDA).
[src:energy-management/decision-making] This area of decision-making, although long established, has attracted the interest of many researchers and practitioners and is still highly debated as there are many MCDA methods which may yield very different results when they are applied to exactly the same data.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] This leads to the formulation of a decision-making paradox.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] Logical decision-making is an important part of all science-based professions, where specialists apply their knowledge in a given area to make informed decisions.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] For example, medical decision-making often involves a diagnosis and the selection of appropriate treatment.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] But naturalistic decision-making research shows that in situations with higher time pressure, higher stakes, or increased ambiguities, experts may use intuitive decision-making rather than structured approaches.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] They may follow a recognition-primed decision that fits their experience, and arrive at a course of action without weighing alternatives.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] The decision-maker's environment can play a part in the decision-making process.
[src:energy-management/decision-making] For example, environmental complexity is a factor that influences cognitive function.
